<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:1">1:1</span></font></b> The book of the genealogy of Jesus Christ, the son of David, the son of Abraham. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:2">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:2">2</span></font></b> Abraham became the father of Isaac, and Isaac became the father of Jacob, and Jacob became the father of Judah and his brothers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:3">3</span></font></b> and Judah became the father of Perez and Zerah by Tamar, and Perez became the father of Hezron, and Hezron became the father of Aram,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Although the Greek text reads &ldquo;Aram,&rdquo; many English versions substitute the Old Testament form of the name, &ldquo;Ram&rdquo; (cf. 1 Chr 2:9; Ruth 4:19), here and in the following verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:4">4</span></font></b> and Aram became the father of Amminadab, and Amminadab became the father of Nahshon, and Nahshon became the father of Salmon, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:5">5</span></font></b> and Salmon became the father of Boaz by Rahab, and Boaz became the father of Obed by Ruth, and Obed became the father of Jesse, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:6">6</span></font></b> and Jesse became the father of David the king. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:7">  And David became the father of Solomon by the <i>[wife]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;wife&rdquo; is not in the Greek text, but is implied idiomatically."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of Uriah, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:7">7</span></font></b> and Solomon became the father of Rehoboam, and Rehoboam became the father of Abijah, and Abijah became the father of Asa,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Greek &ldquo;Asaph,&rdquo; alternately spelled &ldquo;Asa&rdquo; in many English versions here and in the following verse (cf. 1 Chr 3:10)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:8">8</span></font></b> and Asa became the father of Jehoshaphat,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Greek &ldquo;Josaphat&rdquo;; alternately spelled &ldquo;Jehoshaphat&rdquo; in many English versions."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and Jehoshaphat became the father of Joram, and Joram became the father of Uzziah, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:9">9</span></font></b> and Uzziah became the father of Jotham, and Jotham became the father of Ahaz, and Ahaz became the father of Hezekiah, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:10">10</span></font></b> and Hezekiah became the father of Manasseh, and Manasseh became the father of Amon,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The earliest and best Greek manuscripts read &ldquo;Amos,&rdquo; but many English versions use the Old Testament form of the name here, &ldquo;Amon&rdquo; (cf. 2 Kgs 21:18)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and Amon became the father of Josiah, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:11">11</span></font></b> and Josiah became the father of Jechoniah and his brothers, at the time of the deportation to Babylon. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:12">    <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:12">12</span></font></b> And after the deportation to Babylon, Jechoniah became the father of Shealtiel,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Greek &ldquo;Salathiel,&rdquo; but many English versions use the Old Testament form of the name here, &ldquo;Shealtiel&rdquo; (cf. Ezra 3:2)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and Shealtiel became the father of Zerubbabel, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:13">13</span></font></b> and Zerubbabel became the father of Abiud, and Abiud became the father of Eliakim, and Eliakim became the father of Azor, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:14">14</span></font></b> and Azor became the father of Zadok, and Zadok became the father of Achim, and Achim became the father of Eliud, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:15">15</span></font></b> and Eliud became the father of Eleazar, and Eleazar became the father of Matthan, and Matthan became the father of Jacob, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:16">16</span></font></b> and Jacob became the father of Joseph, the husband of Mary by whom<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The Greek relative pronoun is feminine gender and thus refers only to Mary, not Joseph."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was born Jesus, who is called Christ. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:17">    <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:17">17</span></font></b> Therefore all the generations from Abraham to David <i>[are]</i> fourteen generations, and from David to the deportation to Babylon <i>[are]</i> fourteen generations, and from the deportation to Babylon to the Christ <i>[are]</i> fourteen generations. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:18">18</span></font></b> Now the birth of Jesus Christ occurred in this way. His mother Mary had been betrothed to Joseph, <i>[but]</i> before they came together, she was found <u>to be pregnant</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to have in the womb.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by the Holy Spirit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:19">19</span></font></b> So Joseph her husband, being righteous and not wanting to disgrace her, intended to divorce her secretly. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:20">20</span></font></b> But <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;considering&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was considering these things, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared to him in a dream, saying, &ldquo;Joseph, son of David, do not be afraid to take Mary <i>[as]</i> your wife, for what has been conceived in her is from the Holy Spirit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:21">21</span></font></b> And she will give birth to a son, and you will call his name &apos;Jesus,&apos; because he will save his people from their sins.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:22">22</span></font></b> Now all this happened in order that what was spoken by the Lord through the prophet would be fulfilled, saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="1:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:23">23</span></font></b> &ldquo;Behold, the virgin <u>will become pregnant</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;will have in the womb.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will give birth to a son, and they will call his name Emmanuel,&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 7:14."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> which is translated, &ldquo;God with us.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Isa 8:8, 10 in the Greek OT (LXX)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:24">24</span></font></b> And Joseph, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;when&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;woke up&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> woke up from sleep, did as the angel of the Lord commanded him, and he took his wife <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="1:25">25</span></font></b> and <u>did not have sexual relations with</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;did not know.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> her until she gave birth to a son. And he called his name Jesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:1">2:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was born&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus was born in Bethlehem of Judea in the days of Herod the king, behold, wise men from the east came to Jerusalem, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:2">2</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Where is the one who has been born king of the Jews? For we have seen his star at its rising<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or, &ldquo;when it rose&rdquo;; traditionally rendered &ldquo;in the east&rdquo; by many English versions."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and have come to worship him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:3">3</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> King Herod heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was troubled, and all Jerusalem with him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:4">4</span></font></b> and <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;calling together&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> calling together all the chief priests and scribes of the people, he inquired from them where the Christ was to be born. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:5">5</span></font></b> So they said to him, &ldquo;In Bethlehem of Judea, for thus it is written by the prophet, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:6">6</span></font></b> &apos;And you, Bethlehem, land of Judah, are by no means least among the rulers of Judah, for from you will go out a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Mic 5:2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:7">7</span></font></b> Then Herod secretly summoned the wise men <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> determined precisely from them the time <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;appeared&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the star appeared. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:8">8</span></font></b> And he sent them to Bethlehem <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Go, inquire carefully concerning the child, and when you have found <i>[him]</i>, report to me so that I also may come <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;may come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> worship him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:9">9</span></font></b> <i>[After]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;listened to&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they listened to the king, they went out, and behold, the star which they had seen at its rising<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or, &ldquo;when it rose&rdquo;; traditionally rendered &ldquo;in the east&rdquo; by many English versions."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> led them until it came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stood above <i>[the place]</i> where the child was. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:10">10</span></font></b> Now <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the star, they rejoiced <i>[with]</i> very great joy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came into the house, they saw the child with Mary his mother, and they fell down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;fell down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> worshiped him. And opening their treasure boxes, they offered him gifts of gold and frankincense and myrrh. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:12">12</span></font></b> And being warned in a dream not to return to Herod, they went back to their <i>[own]</i> country by another route. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:13">13</span></font></b> Now <i>[after]</i> they had gone away, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph, saying, &ldquo;Get up, take the child and his mother and flee to Egypt, and stay there until I tell you. For Herod is about to seek the child to destroy him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:14">14</span></font></b> So he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took the child and his mother during the night and went away to Egypt. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:15">15</span></font></b> And he was there until the death of Herod, in order that what was said by the Lord through the prophet would be fulfilled, saying, &ldquo;Out of Egypt I called my son.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:16">16</span></font></b> Then Herod, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw that he had been deceived by the wise men, became very angry, and he sent <i>[soldiers]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> executed all the children in Bethlehem and in all the region <i>[around]</i> it from <i>[the age of]</i> two years old and under, according to the time which he had determined precisely from the wise men. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:17">17</span></font></b> Then what was spoken by the prophet Jeremiah was fulfilled, saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:18">18</span></font></b> &ldquo;A voice was heard in Ramah, weeping and great mourning, Rachel weeping <i>[for]</i> her children, and she did not want to be comforted, because <u>they exist no longer</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;they are not.&rdquo;">.<font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Jer 31:15."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="2:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:19">19</span></font></b> Now <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had died&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Herod had died, behold, an angel of the Lord appeared in a dream to Joseph in Egypt, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:20">20</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Get up, take the child and his mother and go to the land of Israel, for those who were seeking the life of the child are dead.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:21">21</span></font></b> So he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took the child and his mother and <u>entered</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;entered into.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the land of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:22">22</span></font></b> But <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that Archelaus was reigning over Judea in place of his father Herod, he was afraid to go there, and being warned in a dream, he took refuge in the regions of Galilee. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="2:23">23</span></font></b> And he came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lived in a town called Nazareth, in order that what was said by the prophets would be fulfilled:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;that&rdquo;; the conjunction could be understood (1) to introduce a direct quotation, serving a function similar to modern English quotation marks, and thus not translated; or (2) to introduce an indirect quotation, in which case it could be translated &ldquo;that he would be called a Nazarene.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;He will be called a Nazarene.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:1">3:1</span></font></b> Now in those days John the Baptist came preaching in the Judean wilderness <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:2">2</span></font></b> and saying, &ldquo;Repent, for the kingdom of heaven has come near!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:3">3</span></font></b> For this is the one who was spoken about by the prophet Isaiah, saying, &ldquo;The voice of one crying out in the wilderness, &apos;Prepare the way of the Lord, make his paths straight.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 40:3."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:4">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:4">4</span></font></b> Now John himself had his clothing made from camel&apos;s hair and a belt made of leather around his waist, and his food was locusts and wild honey. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:5">5</span></font></b> Then Jerusalem and all Judea and all the district around the Jordan were going out to him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:6">6</span></font></b> and they were being baptized by him in the Jordan River <i>[as they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;confessed&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> confessed their sins. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:7">7</span></font></b> But <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw many of the Pharisees and Sadducees coming to his baptism, he said to them, &ldquo;Offspring of vipers! Who warned you to flee from the coming wrath? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:8">8</span></font></b> Therefore produce fruit worthy of repentance! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:9">9</span></font></b> And do not think to say to yourselves, &apos;We have Abraham <i>[as]</i> father.&apos; For I say to you that God is able to raise up children for Abraham from these stones! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:10">10</span></font></b> Already now the ax is positioned at the root of the trees; therefore every tree not producing good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:11">11</span></font></b> I baptize you with water for repentance, but the one who comes after me is more powerful than I <i>[am]</i>, whose sandals I am not worthy to carry. He will baptize you with the Holy Spirit and fire. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:12">12</span></font></b> His winnowing shovel <i>[is]</i> in his hand, and he will clean out his threshing floor and will gather his wheat into the storehouse, but he will burn up the chaff with unquenchable fire.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="3:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:13">13</span></font></b> Then Jesus came from Galilee to the Jordan to John in order to be baptized by him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:14">14</span></font></b> But John tried to prevent<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect verb is understood as conative (&ldquo;tried to&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> him, saying, &ldquo;<u>I need</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;I have need.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to be baptized by you, and do you come to me?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:15">15</span></font></b> But Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Permit <i>[it]</i> now, for in this way it is right for us to fulfill all righteousness.&rdquo; Then he permitted him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:16">16</span></font></b> Now <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was baptized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was baptized, Jesus immediately went up from the water, and behold, the heavens opened<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;opened to him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and he saw the Spirit of God descending like a dove coming<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;and coming.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> upon him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="3:17">17</span></font></b> And behold, <i>[there was]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[there was]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text, but are supplied to make a complete sentence in English."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a voice from heaven saying, &ldquo;This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:1">4:1</span></font></b> Then Jesus was led up into the wilderness by the Spirit to be tempted by the devil, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:2">2</span></font></b> and <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had fasted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had fasted forty days and forty nights, then he was hungry. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:3">3</span></font></b> And the tempter approached <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;If you are the Son of God, order that these stones become bread.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:4">4</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It is written, &apos;Man will not live on bread alone, but on every word that comes out of the mouth of God.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 8:3."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:5">5</span></font></b> Then the devil took him to the holy city<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, Jerusalem."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and placed him on the highest point of the temple <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:6">6</span></font></b> and said to him, &ldquo;If you are the Son of God, throw yourself down! For it is written, &apos;He will command his angels concerning you,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 91:11."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and &apos;On <i>[their]</i> hands they will lift you up, lest you strike your foot against a stone.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 91:12."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:7">7</span></font></b> Jesus said to him, &ldquo;On the other hand it is written, &apos;You are not to put the Lord your God to the test.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 6:16."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:8">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:8">8</span></font></b> Again the devil took him to a very high mountain and showed him all the kingdoms of the world and their glory, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:9">9</span></font></b> and he said to him, &ldquo;I will give to you all these things, if you will fall down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;will fall down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> worship me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:10">10</span></font></b> Then Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Go away, Satan, for it is written, &apos;You shall worship the Lord your God and serve only him.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 6:13."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:11">11</span></font></b> Then the devil left him, and behold, angels came and began ministering to him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:12">12</span></font></b> Now <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that John <u>had been arrested</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;had been handed over.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he withdrew into Galilee. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:13">13</span></font></b> And leaving Nazareth, he went <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lived in Capernaum by the sea, in the region of Zebulun and Naphtali, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:14">14</span></font></b> in order that what was spoken by the prophet Isaiah would be fulfilled, who said, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:15">15</span></font></b> &ldquo;Land of Zebulun and land of Naphtali, <u>toward the sea</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the way of the sea.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on the other side of the Jordan, Galilee of the Gentiles<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nations&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> -- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:16">16</span></font></b> the people who sit in darkness have seen a great light, and the ones who sit in the land and shadow of death, a light has dawned on them.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 9:1."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:17">17</span></font></b> From that time <i>[on]</i>, Jesus began to preach and to say, &ldquo;Repent, because the kingdom of heaven is near.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:18">18</span></font></b> Now <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was walking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was walking beside the Sea of Galilee, he saw two brothers, Simon called Peter and his brother Andrew, throwing a casting net into the sea (for they were fishermen). <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:19">19</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;<u>Follow me</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;come behind me.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and I will make you fishers of people.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:20">20</span></font></b> And immediately they left their nets <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;left&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> followed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:21">21</span></font></b> And going on from there, he saw two other brothers, James the <i>[son]</i> of Zebedee and his brother John, in the boat with their father Zebedee, mending their nets, and he called them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:22">22</span></font></b> And immediately they left the boat and their father <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;left&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> followed him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="4:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:23">23</span></font></b> And he went around through all of Galilee, teaching in their synagogues and proclaiming the good news of the kingdom and healing every disease and every sickness among the people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:24">24</span></font></b> And a report about him went out <u>throughout</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the whole of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Syria, and they brought to him all those <u>who were sick</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having badly.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with various diseases and afflicted by torments, demon-possessed<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;and demon-possessed.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and epileptics and paralytics, and he healed them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="4:25">25</span></font></b> And large crowds followed him from Galilee, Decapolis, Jerusalem, Judea, and from the other side of the Jordan. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:1">5:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the crowds, he went up the mountain and <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sat down, his disciples approached him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:2">2</span></font></b> And opening his mouth he began to teach them, saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:3">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:3">3</span></font></b> &ldquo;Blessed <i>[are]</i> the poor in spirit, because theirs is the kingdom of heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:4">4</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the ones who mourn, because they will be comforted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:5">5</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the meek, because they will inherit the earth. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:6">6</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the ones who hunger and thirst <i>[for]</i> righteousness, because they will be satisfied. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:7">7</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the merciful, because they will be shown mercy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:8">8</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the pure in heart, because they will see God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:9">9</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> the peacemakers, because they will be called sons of God. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:10">10</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[are]</i> those who are persecuted because of righteousness, because theirs is the kingdom of heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:11">11</span></font></b> Blessed are you when they insult you and persecute <i>[you]</i> and say all kinds of evil things against you, lying on account of me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:12">12</span></font></b> Rejoice and be glad, because your reward <i>[is]</i> great in heaven, for in the <i>[same]</i> way they persecuted the prophets before you.</p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:13">13</span></font></b> &ldquo;You are the salt of the earth. But if salt becomes tasteless, by what will it be made salty? It is good for nothing any longer except to be thrown outside <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;thrown&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> trampled under foot by people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:14">14</span></font></b> You are the light of the world. A city located on top of a hill cannot be hidden, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:15">15</span></font></b> nor do they light a lamp and place it under a basket, but on a lampstand, and it shines on all those in the house. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:16">16</span></font></b> In the <i>[same]</i> way let your light shine before people, so that they can see your good works and glorify your Father who is in heaven. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:17">17</span></font></b> &ldquo;Do not think that I have come to destroy the law or the prophets. I have not come to destroy <i>[them]</i> but to fulfill <i>[them]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:18">18</span></font></b> For truly I say to you, until heaven and earth pass away, not one tiny letter or one stroke of a letter will pass away from the law until all takes place. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:19">19</span></font></b> Therefore whoever abolishes one of the least of these commandments and teaches people to do so will be called least in the kingdom of heaven, but whoever keeps <i>[them]</i> and teaches <i>[them]</i>, this person will be called great in the kingdom of heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:20">20</span></font></b> For I say to you that unless your righteousness greatly surpasses <i>[that]</i> of the scribes and Pharisees, you will never enter into the kingdom of heaven. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:21">21</span></font></b> &ldquo;You have heard that it was said to the <u>people of old</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;ancients.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;Do not commit murder,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 20:13; Deut 5:17."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and &apos;whoever commits murder will be subject to judgment.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:22">22</span></font></b> But I say to you that everyone who is angry at his brother will be subject to judgment, and whoever says to his brother, &apos;Stupid fool!&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Greek &ldquo;Raca,&rdquo; a term of verbal abuse involving lack of intelligence."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> will be subject to the council, and whoever says, &apos;Obstinate fool!&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Perhaps with the idea of obstinate, godless foolishness; some take the word to be a Greek transliteration of the Hebrew word for &ldquo;rebel&rdquo; (Deut 21:18, 20)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> will be subject to fiery hell. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:23">23</span></font></b> Therefore if you present your gift at the altar and there remember that your brother has something against you, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:24">24</span></font></b> leave your gift there before the altar and first go be reconciled to your brother, and then come <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> present your gift. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:25">25</span></font></b> <u>Settle the case quickly with your accuser</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;be making friends quickly with your accuser.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> while you are with him on the way, lest your accuser hand you over to the judge, and the judge to the officer, and you be thrown into prison. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:26">26</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, you will never come out of there until you have paid back the last penny! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:27">27</span></font></b> &ldquo;You have heard that it was said, &apos;Do not commit adultery.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 20:14; Deut 5:17."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:28">28</span></font></b> But I say to you that everyone who looks at a woman to lust for her has already committed adultery with her in his heart. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:29">29</span></font></b> And if your right eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw <i>[it]</i> from you! For it is better for you that one of your members be destroyed than your whole body be thrown into hell. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:30">30</span></font></b> And if your right hand causes you to sin, cut it off and throw <i>[it]</i> from you! For it is better for you that one of your limbs be destroyed than your whole body go into hell. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:31">31</span></font></b> &ldquo;And it was said, &apos;Whoever divorces his wife must give her a certificate of divorce.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 24:1."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:32">32</span></font></b> But I say to you that everyone who divorces his wife, except for a matter of sexual immorality, causes her to commit adultery, and whoever marries a divorced woman commits adultery. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:33">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:33">33</span></font></b> &ldquo;Again you have heard that it was said to the <u>people of old</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;ancients.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;Do not swear falsely,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;do not break your oath.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> but fulfill your oaths to the Lord.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Lev 19:12."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:34">34</span></font></b> But I say to you, do not swear at all, either by heaven, because it is the throne of God, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:35">35</span></font></b> or by the earth, because it is the footstool of his feet, or by Jerusalem, because it is the city of the great king. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:36">36</span></font></b> And do not swear by your head, because you are not able to make one hair white or black. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:37">37</span></font></b> But let your statement be &apos;Yes, yes; no, no,&apos; and anything beyond these is from the evil one.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;is of evil.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:38">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:38">38</span></font></b> &ldquo;You have heard that it was said, &apos;An eye for an eye and a tooth for a tooth.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 21:24; Lev 24:20."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:39">39</span></font></b> But I say to you, do not resist the evildoer, but whoever strikes you on the right cheek,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;your right cheek.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> turn the other to him also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:40">40</span></font></b> And the one who wants to go to court with you and take your tunic, <u>let him have</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;leave to him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> your outer garment also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:41">41</span></font></b> And whoever forces you to go one mile,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A Roman mile was originally a thousand paces, but was later fixed at eight stades (1,478.5 meters)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> go with him two. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:42">42</span></font></b> Give to the one who asks you, and do not turn away from the one who wants to borrow from you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="5:43">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:43">43</span></font></b> &ldquo;You have heard that it was said, &apos;Love your neighbor&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Lev 19:18."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and &apos;Hate your enemy.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Deut 23:3-6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:44">44</span></font></b> But I say to you, love your enemies and pray for those who persecute you, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:45">45</span></font></b> in order that you may be sons of your Father who is in heaven, because he causes his sun to rise on the evil and the good, and he sends rain on the just and the unjust. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:46">46</span></font></b> For if you love those who love you, what reward do you have? Do not the tax collectors also do the same? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:47">47</span></font></b> And if you greet only your brothers, what are you doing that is remarkable? Do not the Gentiles also do the same? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="5:48">48</span></font></b> Therefore you be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:1">6:1</span></font></b> &ldquo;And take care not to practice your righteousness before people to be seen by them; <u>otherwise</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;but if not.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you have no reward from your Father who is in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:2">2</span></font></b> Therefore whenever you practice charitable giving, do not sound a trumpet in front of you, as the hypocrites do in the synagogues and in the streets, in order that they may be praised by people. Truly I say to you, they have received their reward in full! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:3">3</span></font></b> But you, <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;practice&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> practice charitable giving, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:4">4</span></font></b> in order that your charitable giving may be in secret, and your Father who sees in secret will reward you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:5">5</span></font></b> And whenever you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, because they love to stand <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stand&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> pray in the synagogues and on the corners of the streets, in order that they may be seen by people. Truly I say to you, they have received their reward in full! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:6">6</span></font></b> But whenever you pray, enter into your inner room and shut your door <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;shut&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> pray to your Father who is in secret, and your Father who sees in secret will reward you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:7">7</span></font></b> &ldquo;But <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;pray&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> pray, do not babble repetitiously like the pagans, for they think that because of their many words they will be heard. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:8">8</span></font></b> Therefore do not be like them, for your Father knows <u>what you need</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;of what you have need.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> before you ask him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:9">9</span></font></b> Therefore you pray in this way: &ldquo;Our Father who is in heaven, may your name be treated as holy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:10">10</span></font></b> May your kingdom come, may your will be done on earth as <i>[it is]</i> in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:11">11</span></font></b> Give us today our daily bread, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:12">12</span></font></b> and forgive us our debts, as we also have forgiven our debtors. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:13">13</span></font></b> And do not bring us into temptation, but deliver us from the evil one.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;evil&rdquo;; most later Greek manuscripts add the phrase &ldquo;for yours is the kingdom and the power and the glory forever, amen.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:14">14</span></font></b> For if you forgive people their sins, your heavenly Father will also forgive you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:15">15</span></font></b> But if you do not forgive people, neither will your Father forgive your sins. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;Whenever you fast, do not be sullen like the hypocrites, for they make their faces unrecognizable in order that they may be seen fasting by people. Truly I say to you, they have received their reward in full! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:17">17</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;fasting&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you are fasting, <u>put olive oil on your head</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;anoint your head.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and wash your face <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:18">18</span></font></b> so that you will not be seen by people as fasting, but to your Father who is in secret, and your Father who sees in secret will reward you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:19">19</span></font></b> &ldquo;Do not store up for yourselves treasures on earth, where moth and consuming <i>[insect]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Traditionally &ldquo;rust,&rdquo; but more likely in this context along with &ldquo;moth&rdquo; the term refers to &ldquo;eating&rdquo; by other types of insects or vermin."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> destroy and where thieves break in and steal, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:20">20</span></font></b> but store up for yourselves treasures in heaven, where neither moth nor consuming <i>[insect]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Traditionally &ldquo;rust,&rdquo; but more likely in this context along with &ldquo;moth&rdquo; the term refers to &ldquo;eating&rdquo; by other types of insects or vermin."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> destroy and where thieves do not break in or steal. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:21">21</span></font></b> For where your treasure is, there your heart will be also. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:22">22</span></font></b> &ldquo;The eye is the lamp of the body. Therefore if your eye is sincere, your whole body will be full of light. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:23">23</span></font></b> But if your eye is evil, your whole body will be dark. Therefore if the light in you is darkness, how great <i>[is]</i> the darkness! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:24">24</span></font></b> &ldquo;No one is able to serve two masters. For either he will hate the one and love the other, or he will be devoted to one and despise the other. You are not able to serve God and money.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Traditionally transliterated from the Greek as &ldquo;mammon.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="6:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:25">25</span></font></b> &ldquo;For this <i>[reason]</i> I say to you, do not be anxious for your life, what you will eat,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts add &ldquo;or what you will drink&rdquo;; other later manuscripts add &ldquo;and what you will drink.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and not for your body, what you will wear. Is your life not more than food and your body <i>[more than]</i> clothing? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:26">26</span></font></b> Consider the birds of the sky, that they do not sow or reap or gather <i>[produce]</i> into barns, and your heavenly Father feeds them. Are you not worth more than they <i>[are]</i>? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:27">27</span></font></b> And who among you, <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;being anxious&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> being anxious, is able to add one hour<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;cubit.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to his life span? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:28">28</span></font></b> And why are you anxious about clothing? Observe the lilies of the field, how they grow: they do not toil or spin, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:29">29</span></font></b> but I say to you that not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of these. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:30">30</span></font></b> But if God dresses the grass of the field in this way, <i>[although it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;is&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is <i>[here]</i> today and tomorrow is thrown into the oven, will he not <i>[do so]</i> much more <i>[for]</i> you, you of little faith? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:31">31</span></font></b> Therefore do not be anxious, saying, &apos;What will we eat?&apos; or &apos;What will we drink?&apos; or &apos;What will we wear?,&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:32">32</span></font></b> for the pagans seek after all these <i>[things]</i>. For your heavenly Father knows that you need all these <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:33">33</span></font></b> But seek first his kingdom and righteousness,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;the kingdom of God and his righteousness.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and all these <i>[things]</i> will be added to you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="6:34">34</span></font></b> Therefore do not be anxious for tomorrow, because tomorrow will be anxious for itself. <u>Each day has enough trouble of its own.</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;sufficient for the day its trouble.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:1">7:1</span></font></b> &ldquo;Do not judge, so that you will not be judged. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:2">2</span></font></b> For by what judgment you judge, you will be judged, and by what measure you measure out, it will be measured out to you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:3">3</span></font></b> And why do you see the speck <i>[that is]</i> in your brother&apos;s eye, but do not notice the beam of wood in your <i>[own]</i> eye? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:4">4</span></font></b> Or how will you say to your brother, &apos;Allow <i>[me]</i> to remove the speck from your eye,&apos; and behold, the beam of wood <i>[is]</i> in your <i>[own]</i> eye? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:5">5</span></font></b> Hypocrite! First remove the beam of wood from your <i>[own]</i> eye and then you will see clearly to remove the speck from your brother&apos;s eye! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:6">6</span></font></b> &ldquo;Do not give what is holy to dogs, or throw your pearls in front of pigs, lest they trample them with their feet, and turn around <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;turn around&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tear you to pieces. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:7">7</span></font></b> &ldquo;Ask and it will be given to you; seek and you will find; knock and it will be opened for you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:8">8</span></font></b> For everyone who asks receives, and the one who seeks finds, and to the one who knocks it will be opened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:9">9</span></font></b> Or what man is <i>[there]</i> among you, <i>[if]</i> his son will ask him <i>[for]</i> bread, will give him a stone? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:10">10</span></font></b> Or also <i>[if]</i> he will ask for a fish, will give him a snake? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:11">11</span></font></b> Therefore if you, <i>[although you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are evil, know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more will your Father who is in heaven give good things to those who ask him? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:12">12</span></font></b> Therefore <i>[in]</i> all <i>[things]</i>, whatever you want that people should do to you, thus also you do to them. For this is the law and the prophets. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:13">13</span></font></b> &ldquo;Enter through the narrow gate, because broad <i>[is]</i> the gate and spacious <i>[is]</i> the road that leads to destruction, and there are many who enter through it, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:14">14</span></font></b> because narrow<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;how narrow.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[is]</i> the gate and constricted <i>[is]</i> the road that leads to life, and there are few who find it! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:15">15</span></font></b> &ldquo;Beware of false prophets who come to you in sheep&apos;s clothing, but inside are ravenous wolves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:16">16</span></font></b> You will recognize them by their fruits: they do not gather grapes from thorn bushes or figs from thistles, <i>[do they]</i>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The negative construction in Greek anticipates a negative answer here, indicated by &ldquo;<i>[do they]</i>.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:17">17</span></font></b> In the <i>[same]</i> way, every good tree produces good fruit, but a bad tree produces bad fruit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:18">18</span></font></b> A good tree is not able to produce bad fruit, nor a bad tree to produce good fruit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:19">19</span></font></b> Every tree that does not produce good fruit is cut down and thrown into the fire. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:20">20</span></font></b> As a result, you will recognize them by their fruits. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:21">21</span></font></b> &ldquo;Not everyone who says to me, &apos;Lord, Lord,&apos; will enter into the kingdom of heaven, but the one who does the will of my Father who is in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:22">22</span></font></b> On that day many will say to me, &apos;Lord, Lord, did we not prophesy in your name, and expel demons in your name, and perform many miracles in your name?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:23">23</span></font></b> And then <u>I will say to them plainly</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;I will declare to them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;I never knew you. Depart from me, you who practice lawlessness!&apos; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:24">24</span></font></b> &ldquo;Therefore everyone who hears these words of mine and does them will be like a wise man who built his house on the rock. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:25">25</span></font></b> And the rain came down and the rivers came and the winds blew and beat against that house, and it did not collapse, because its foundation was laid on the rock. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:26">26</span></font></b> And everyone who hears these words of mine and does not do them will be like a foolish man who built his house on the sand. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:27">27</span></font></b> And the rain came down and the rivers came and the winds blew and beat against that house, and it collapsed, and its fall was great.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="7:28">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:28">28</span></font></b> And it happened when Jesus finished these words the crowds were amazed at his teaching, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="7:29">29</span></font></b> because he was teaching them like one who had authority, and not like their scribes. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:1">8:1</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came down&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he came down from the mountain, large crowds followed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:2">2</span></font></b> And behold, a leper approached <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> worshiped him, saying, &ldquo;Lord, if you are willing, you are able to make me clean.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:3">3</span></font></b> And extending his hand he touched him, saying, &ldquo;I am willing, be clean.&rdquo; And immediately his leprosy was cleansed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:4">4</span></font></b> And Jesus said to him, &ldquo;See that you tell no one, but go, show yourself to the priest and offer the gift that Moses commanded, for a testimony to them.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:5">5</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he entered Capernaum, a centurion approached him, appealing to him <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:6">6</span></font></b> and saying, &ldquo;Lord, my slave<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Traditionally &ldquo;servant&rdquo;; the Greek term here is one often used of a slave who was regarded with some degree of affection, possibly a personal servant (the parallel passage in Luke 7:7 uses the more common term for slave)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is lying paralyzed in my<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> house, terribly tormented!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:7">7</span></font></b> And he said to him, &ldquo;I will come <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heal him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:8">8</span></font></b> And the centurion answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Lord, I am not worthy that you should come in under my roof. But only say the word and my slave will be healed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:9">9</span></font></b> For I also am a man under authority who has soldiers under me, and I say to this one, &apos;Go!&apos; and he goes, and to another one, &apos;Come!&apos; and he comes, and to my slave, &apos;Do this!&apos; and he does <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation (see the parallel in Luke 7:8).">.<font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:10">10</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was astonished, and said to those who were following <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Truly I say to you, I have found such great faith with no one in Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:11">11</span></font></b> But I say to you that many will come from east and west and <u>be seated at the banquet</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;recline at table.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with Abraham and Isaac and Jacob in the kingdom of heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:12">12</span></font></b> But the sons of the kingdom will be thrown out into the outer darkness. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:13">13</span></font></b> And Jesus said to the centurion, &ldquo;Go, as you have believed it will be done for you.&rdquo; And the slave<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Many later manuscripts have &ldquo;his slave.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was healed at that hour. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus came into Peter&apos;s house, he saw his mother-in-law lying down and suffering with a fever. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:15">15</span></font></b> And he touched her hand and the fever left her, and she got up and began to serve him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:16">16</span></font></b> Now <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was evening, they brought to him many who were demon-possessed, and he expelled the spirits with a word. And he healed all <u>those who were sick</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those who were having badly.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:17">17</span></font></b> in order that what was spoken through the prophet Isaiah would be fulfilled, who said, &ldquo;He himself took away our sicknesses, and carried away our diseases.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 53:4."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:18">18</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus saw many crowds<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;a crowd.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> around him, he gave orders to depart to the other side.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, the other side of the Sea of Galilee."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:19">19</span></font></b> And a scribe approached <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Teacher, I will follow you wherever you go!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:20">20</span></font></b> And Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Foxes have dens and birds of the sky <i>[have]</i> nests, but the Son of Man has no place to lay his head.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:21">21</span></font></b> And another of the disciples<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;of his disciples.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Lord, allow me first to go and bury my father.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:22">22</span></font></b> But Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Follow me, and leave the dead to bury their own dead!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;got&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he got into the boat, his disciples followed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:24">24</span></font></b> And behold, a great storm arose on the sea, so that the boat was being inundated by the waves, but he himself was asleep. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:25">25</span></font></b> And they came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> woke him, saying, &ldquo;Lord, save <i>[us]</i>!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> We are perishing!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:26">26</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Why are you fearful, <i>[you]</i> of little faith?&rdquo; Then he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rebuked the winds and the sea and there was a great calm. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:27">27</span></font></b> And the men were astonished, saying, &ldquo;What sort of <i>[man]</i> is this, that even the winds and the sea obey him?&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="8:28">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:28">28</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he came to the other side,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, the other side of the Sea of Galilee."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the region of the Gadarenes,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Many manuscripts read &ldquo;Gergesenes&rdquo;; others read &ldquo;Gerasenes&rdquo; (see Luke 8:26)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> two demon-possessed men coming from among the tombs met him, very violent, so that no one was able to pass by along that road. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:29">29</span></font></b> And behold, they cried out, saying, &ldquo;<u>What do you have to do with us</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;what to us and to you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Son of God? Have you come here to torment us before the time?&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, before the appointed time of judgment."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:30">30</span></font></b> Now a long way from them a large herd of pigs was feeding. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:31">31</span></font></b> So the demons implored him, saying, &ldquo;If you are going to expel us, send us into the herd of pigs.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:32">32</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Go!&rdquo; So they departed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went into the pigs, and behold, the whole herd rushed headlong down the steep slope into the sea and drowned in the water. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:33">33</span></font></b> Now the herdsmen fled and went into the town <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported everything, including the things concerning the demon-possessed men. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="8:34">34</span></font></b> And behold, the whole town came out to meet Jesus, and <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw him, they implored <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that he would depart from their region. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:1">9:1</span></font></b> And getting into a boat, he crossed over and came to his own town.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A reference to Capernaum."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:2">2</span></font></b> And behold, they brought to him a paralytic lying on a stretcher, and <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus saw their faith, he said to the paralytic, &ldquo;Have courage, child, your sins are forgiven.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:3">3</span></font></b> And behold, some of the scribes said to themselves, &ldquo;This man is blaspheming!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:4">4</span></font></b> And knowing<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;perceiving.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> their thoughts, Jesus said, &ldquo;Why do you think evil in your hearts? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:5">5</span></font></b> For which is easier to say, &apos;Your sins are forgiven,&apos; or to say, &apos;Get up and walk&apos;? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:6">6</span></font></b> But in order that you may know that the Son of Man has authority on earth to forgive sins,&rdquo; then he said to the paralytic, &ldquo;Get up, pick up your stretcher and go to your home.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:7">7</span></font></b> And he got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went to his home. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:8">8</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the crowds saw <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were afraid and glorified God who had given such authority to men. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus was going away from there, he saw a man called Matthew sitting at the tax booth and said to him, &ldquo;Follow me!&rdquo; And he stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> followed him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:10">10</span></font></b> And it happened <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was dining&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he <u>was dining</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;was reclining at table.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the house, behold, many tax collectors and sinners were coming <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;were coming&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>dining</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;reclining at table.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with Jesus and his disciples. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Pharisees began to say to his disciples, &ldquo;Why does your teacher eat with tax collectors and sinners?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he said, &ldquo;Those who are healthy do not have need of a physician, but those <u>who are sick</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having badly.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:13">13</span></font></b> But go <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> learn what it means, &ldquo;I want mercy and not sacrifice.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Hos 6:6 (see also Matt 12:7)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> For I did not come to call the righteous, but sinners.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:14">14</span></font></b> Then the disciples of John<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, John the Baptist."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> approached him, saying, &ldquo;Why do we and the Pharisees fast often, but your disciples do not fast?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:15">15</span></font></b> And Jesus said to them, &ldquo;<u>The bridegroom&apos;s attendants</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the sons of the bridal chamber.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are not able to mourn as long as the bridegroom is with them. But days are coming when the bridegroom is taken away from them, and then they will fast. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:16">16</span></font></b> But no one puts a patch of unshrunken cloth on an old garment, for its patch pulls away from the garment, and the tear becomes worse. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:17">17</span></font></b> Nor do they put new wine into old wineskins. <u>Otherwise</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;but if not.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the wineskins burst and the wine is spilled, and the wineskins are destroyed. But they put new wine into new wineskins and both are preserved.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:18">18</span></font></b> <i>[As]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was saying&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was saying these <i>[things]</i> to them, behold, one of the rulers came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knelt down before him, saying, &ldquo;My daughter has just now died, but come, place your hand on her and she will live!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:19">19</span></font></b> And Jesus and his disciples got up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;got up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> followed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:20">20</span></font></b> And behold, a woman who had been suffering with a hemorrhage twelve years approached from behind <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> touched the edge<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;tassel.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of his cloak, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:21">21</span></font></b> for she said to herself, &ldquo;If only I touch his cloak I will be healed.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:22">22</span></font></b> But Jesus, turning around and seeing her, said, &ldquo;Have courage, daughter! Your faith has healed you.&rdquo; And the woman was healed from that hour. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus came into the ruler&apos;s house and saw the flute players and the disorderly crowd, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:24">24</span></font></b> he said, &ldquo;Go away, because the girl is not dead, but is sleeping.&rdquo; And they ridiculed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:25">25</span></font></b> But when the crowd had been sent out, he entered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took her hand, and the girl got up. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:26">26</span></font></b> And this report went out into that whole region. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;going away&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus was going away from there, two blind men followed him, crying out and saying, &ldquo;Have mercy on us, Son of David!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:28">28</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came into the house, the blind men approached him, and Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Do you believe that I am able to do this?&rdquo; They said to him, &ldquo;Yes, Lord.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:29">29</span></font></b> Then he touched their eyes, saying, &ldquo;According to your faith let it be done for you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:30">30</span></font></b> And their eyes were opened, and Jesus sternly warned them, saying, &ldquo;See <i>[that]</i> no one finds out.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:31">31</span></font></b> But they went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spread the report about him in that whole region. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:32">32</span></font></b> Now <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going away&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were going away, behold, they brought to him a demon-possessed man <i>[who was]</i> unable to speak. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:33">33</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had been expelled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the demon had been expelled, the one who had been mute spoke, and the crowds were astonished, saying, &ldquo;<u>This has never been seen before</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;never has it been seen thus.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in Israel!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:34">34</span></font></b> But the Pharisees were saying,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;began to say.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;By the ruler of demons he expels the demons!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="9:35">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:35">35</span></font></b> And Jesus was going around all the towns and the villages, teaching in their synagogues and proclaiming the good news of the kingdom and healing every<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;every kind of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> disease and every<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;every kind of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sickness. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:36">36</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the crowds, he had compassion for them, because they were weary and dejected, like sheep that did not have a shepherd. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:37">37</span></font></b> Then he said to his disciples, &ldquo;The harvest <i>[is]</i> plentiful, but the workers <i>[are]</i> few. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="9:38">38</span></font></b> Therefore ask the Lord of the harvest that he send out workers into his harvest.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:1">10:1</span></font></b> And summoning his twelve disciples, he gave them authority over unclean spirits, so that they could expel <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and could heal every<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;every kind of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> disease and every<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;every kind of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sickness. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:2">2</span></font></b> Now these are the names of the twelve apostles: first Simon who is called Peter, and Andrew his brother, James<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;and James.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the <i>[son]</i> of Zebedee, and John his brother, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:3">3</span></font></b> Philip, and Bartholomew, Thomas, and Matthew the tax collector, James the <i>[son]</i> of Alphaeus, and Thaddaeus, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:4">4</span></font></b> Simon the Zealot,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the Cananean,&rdquo; but according to BDAG 507 s.v., this term has no relation at all to the geographical terms for Cana or Canaan, but is derived from the Aramaic term for &ldquo;enthusiast, zealot&rdquo; (see Luke 6:15; Acts 1:13)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and Judas Iscariot--the one who also betrayed him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:5">5</span></font></b> Jesus sent out these twelve, instructing them saying, &ldquo;Do not go on the road to the Gentiles, and do not enter into a city of the Samaritans, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:6">6</span></font></b> but go instead to the lost sheep of the house of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[as you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are going&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are going, preach, saying, &apos;The kingdom of heaven has come near!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:8">8</span></font></b> Heal those who are sick, raise the dead, cleanse lepers, expel demons. Freely you have received; freely give. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:9">9</span></font></b> Do not procure gold or silver or copper for your belts. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:10">10</span></font></b> Do not <i>[take]</i> a traveler&apos;s bag for the road, or two tunics, or sandals, or a staff, for the worker <i>[is]</i> deserving of his provisions. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:11">11</span></font></b> And into whatever town or village you enter, inquire who in it is worthy, and stay <i>[there]</i> until you depart. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;enter&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> enter into the house, greet it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:13">13</span></font></b> And if the house is worthy, let your peace come upon it, but if it is not worthy, let your peace return to you. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:14">14</span></font></b> And whoever does not welcome you or listen to your words, shake off the dust from your feet <i>[as you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are going&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are going out of that house or <i>[that]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A repetition of &ldquo;that&rdquo; is supplied in English; the single Greek term is understood to modify both &ldquo;house&rdquo; and &ldquo;town.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> town. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:15">15</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, it will be more bearable for the region of Sodom and Gomorrah on the day of judgment than for that town! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;Behold, I am sending you out like sheep in the midst of wolves. Therefore be wise as serpents and innocent as doves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:17">17</span></font></b> But beware of people, because they will hand you over to councils, and they will flog you in their synagogues. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:18">18</span></font></b> And you will be brought before both governors and kings because of me, for a witness to them and to the Gentiles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:19">19</span></font></b> But whenever they hand you over, do not be anxious how <i>[to speak]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[to speak]</i>&rdquo; has been supplied for stylistic reasons, since &ldquo;how to speak&rdquo; is more natural in English than &ldquo;how to say&rdquo;; in Greek the same verb works with both expressions (&ldquo;how or what you should say&rdquo;) and also occurs again at the end of the verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> or what you should say, for what you should say will be given to you at that hour. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:20">20</span></font></b> For you are not the ones who are speaking, but the Spirit of your Father <i>[who is]</i> speaking through you. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:21">21</span></font></b> &ldquo;And brother will hand over brother to death, and a father <i>[his]</i> children, and children will rise up against parents and have them put to death, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:22">22</span></font></b> and you will be hated by everyone because of my name. But the one who endures to the end--this one will be saved. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:23">23</span></font></b> And whenever they persecute you in this town, flee to another, for truly I say to you, you will never finish <i>[going through]</i> the towns of Israel until the Son of Man comes. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:24">24</span></font></b> &ldquo;A disciple is not superior to his teacher, nor a slave superior to his master. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:25">25</span></font></b> <i>[It is]</i> enough for the disciple that he become like his teacher, and the slave like his master. If they have called the master of the house Beelzebul, how much more the members of his household? </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:26">26</span></font></b> &ldquo;Therefore do not be afraid of them, because nothing is hidden that will not be revealed, and nothing secret that will not become known. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:27">27</span></font></b> What I say to you in the dark, tell in the light, and what you hear in your ear, proclaim on the housetops. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:28">28</span></font></b> And do not be afraid of those who kill the body but are not able to kill the soul, but instead be afraid of the one who is able to destroy both soul and body in hell. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:29">29</span></font></b> Are not two sparrows sold for a penny?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally, &ldquo;an assarion,&rdquo; a Roman coin worth about 1/16 of a denarius."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> And one of them will not fall to the ground <u>without the knowledge and consent</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;without&rdquo;; the phrase &ldquo;the knowledge and consent&rdquo; is implied when this term is used of God."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of your Father. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:30">30</span></font></b> And even the hairs of your head are all numbered! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:31">31</span></font></b> Therefore do not be afraid; you are worth more than many sparrows. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:32">32</span></font></b> &ldquo;Therefore everyone who acknowledges me before people, I also will acknowledge him before my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:33">33</span></font></b> But whoever denies me before people, I also will deny him before my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:34">34</span></font></b> &ldquo;Do not think that I have come to bring peace on the earth! I have not come to bring peace, but a sword. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:35">35</span></font></b> For I have come to turn a man against his father, and a daughter against her mother, and a daughter-in-law against her mother-in-law. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:36">36</span></font></b> And the enemies of a man <i>[will be]</i> the members of his household.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Mic 7:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:37">37</span></font></b> The one who loves father or mother more than me is not worthy of me, and the one who loves son or daughter more than me is not worthy of me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:38">38</span></font></b> And whoever does not take up his cross and follow me is not worthy of me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:39">39</span></font></b> The one who finds his life will lose it, and the one who loses his life because of me will find it. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="10:40">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:40">40</span></font></b> &ldquo;The one who receives you receives me, and the one who receives me receives the one who sent me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:41">41</span></font></b> The one who receives a prophet in the name of a prophet will receive a prophet&apos;s reward, and the one who receives a righteous person in the name of a righteous person will receive a righteous person&apos;s reward. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="10:42">42</span></font></b> And whoever gives one of these little ones only a cup of cold water to drink in the name of a disciple, truly I say to you, he will never lose his reward.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:1">11:1</span></font></b> And it happened that when Jesus had finished giving orders to his twelve disciples, he went on from there to teach and to preach in their towns. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:2">2</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> John<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, John the Baptist."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard in prison the deeds of Christ, he sent <i>[word]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by his disciples <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:3">3</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo; in the previous verse) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Are you the one who is to come, or should we look for another?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:4">4</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Go <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tell John what you hear and see: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:5">5</span></font></b> the blind receive sight and the lame walk, lepers are cleansed and the deaf hear, and the dead are raised, and the poor have good news announced to <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:6">6</span></font></b> And whoever is not offended by me is blessed.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:7">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:7">7</span></font></b> Now <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going away&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> these were going away, Jesus began to speak to the crowds concerning John: &ldquo;What did you go out into the wilderness to see? A reed shaken by the wind? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:8">8</span></font></b> But what did you go out to see? A man dressed in soft clothing? Behold, those who wear soft clothing are in the houses of kings. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:9">9</span></font></b> But why did you go out? To see a prophet?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;But what did you go out to see? A prophet?.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Yes, I tell you, and even more than a prophet! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:10">10</span></font></b> It is this man about whom it is written: &apos;Behold, I am sending my messenger before your face, who will prepare your way before you.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Mal 3:1; cf. Mark 1:2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:11">11</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, among <i>[those]</i> born of women there has not arisen <i>[one]</i> greater than John the Baptist. But the one who is least in the kingdom of heaven is greater than he. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:12">12</span></font></b> But from the days of John the Baptist until now, the kingdom of heaven is treated violently, and the violent claim<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;seize.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:13">13</span></font></b> For all the prophets and the law prophesied until John, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:14">14</span></font></b> and if you are willing to accept <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he is Elijah, the one who is going to come. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:15">15</span></font></b> The one who has ears, let him hear! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;But to what shall I compare this generation? It is like children sitting in the marketplaces who call out to one another, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:17">17</span></font></b> saying, &apos;We played the flute for you and you did not dance; we sang a lament and you did not mourn.&apos;</p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:18">18</span></font></b> For John came neither eating nor drinking, and they say, &apos;He has a demon!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:19">19</span></font></b> The Son of Man came eating and drinking, and they say, &apos;Behold, a man <i>[who is]</i> a glutton and a drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners!&apos; But wisdom is vindicated by her deeds.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Many Greek manuscripts, including most later ones, read &ldquo;children.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:20">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:20">20</span></font></b> Then he began to reproach the towns in which the majority of his miracles had been done, because they did not repent: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:21">21</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, Chorazin! Woe to you, Bethsaida! For if the miracles done in you had been done in Tyre and Sidon, they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:22">22</span></font></b> Nevertheless I tell you, it will be more bearable for Tyre and for Sidon on the day of judgment than for you! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:23">23</span></font></b> And you, Capernaum, will you be exalted to heaven? No, you will be brought down to Hades! For if the miracles done in you had been done in Sodom, it would have remained until today. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:24">24</span></font></b> Nevertheless I tell you that it will be more bearable for the region of Sodom on the day of judgment than for you!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="11:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:25">25</span></font></b> At that time Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;I praise you, Father, Lord of heaven and earth, because you have hidden these <i>[things]</i> from the wise and intelligent, and have revealed them to young children.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or perhaps &ldquo;to the childlike,&rdquo; or &ldquo;to the innocent.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:26">26</span></font></b> Yes, Father, for <i>[to do]</i> so <u>was your gracious will</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;was pleasing before you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:27">27</span></font></b> All <i>[things]</i> have been handed over to me by my Father, and no one knows the Son except the Father, and no one knows the Father except the Son and <u>anyone to whom</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to whomever.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Son wants to reveal <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:28">28</span></font></b> Come to me, all <i>[of you]</i> who labor and are burdened, and I will give you rest. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:29">29</span></font></b> Take my yoke on you and learn from me, for I am gentle and humble in heart, and you will find rest for your souls. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="11:30">30</span></font></b> For my yoke <i>[is]</i> easy to carry and my burden is light.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:1">12:1</span></font></b> At that time Jesus went through the grain fields on the Sabbath. And his disciples were hungry, and they began to pluck off heads of grain and eat <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:2">2</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Pharisees saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they said to him, &ldquo;Behold, your disciples are doing what it is not permitted to do on the Sabbath!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:3">3</span></font></b> So he said to them, &ldquo;Have you not read what David did when he was hungry, and those with him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:4">4</span></font></b> how he entered into the house of God and ate the bread of the presentation, which it was not permitted for him or for those with him to eat, but only for the priests? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:5">5</span></font></b> Or have you not read in the law that on the Sabbath the priests in the temple violate the sanctity of the Sabbath and are guiltless? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:6">6</span></font></b> But I tell you that <i>[something]</i> greater than the temple is here! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:7">7</span></font></b> And if you had known what <u>it means</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;it is.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;I want mercy and not sacrifice,&apos; you would not have condemned the guiltless. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:8">8</span></font></b> For the Son of Man is lord of the Sabbath.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:9">9</span></font></b> And going on from there he came into their synagogue. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:10">10</span></font></b> And behold, <i>[there was]</i> a man who had a withered hand, and they asked him, saying, &ldquo;Is it permitted to heal on the Sabbath?&rdquo; in order that they could accuse him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:11">11</span></font></b> But he said to them, &ldquo;What man will there be among you who will have one sheep and if this one fell into a pit on the Sabbath, will not take hold of it and lift <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:12">12</span></font></b> Then to what degree <i>[is]</i> a man worth more than a sheep? So then, it is permitted to do good on the Sabbath.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:13">13</span></font></b> Then he said to the man, &ldquo;Stretch out your hand,&rdquo; and he stretched <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out, and it was restored <i>[as]</i> healthy as the other <i>[one]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:14">14</span></font></b> But the Pharisees went out <u>and plotted</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;taking counsel.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> against him in order that they could destroy him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:15">15</span></font></b> Now Jesus, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;learned&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> learned of <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> withdrew from there, and many<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;many crowds.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> followed him, and he healed them all. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:16">16</span></font></b> And he warned them that they should not <u>reveal his identity</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;make him known.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:17">17</span></font></b> in order that what was spoken through the prophet Isaiah would be fulfilled, who said, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:18">18</span></font></b> &ldquo;Behold my servant whom I have chosen, my beloved in whom my soul is well pleased. I will put my Spirit on him, and he will proclaim justice to the Gentiles. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:19">19</span></font></b> He will not quarrel or cry out, nor will anyone hear his voice in the streets. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:20">20</span></font></b> A crushed reed he will not break, and a smoldering wick he will not extinguish, until he brings justice to victory. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:21">21</span></font></b> And in his name the Gentiles<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;the nations&rdquo;; the same Greek word (in the plural) can be translated as &ldquo;nations,&rdquo; &ldquo;Gentiles,&rdquo; or &ldquo;pagans.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> will hope.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Verses 18-21 are a quotation from Isa 42:1-4."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:22">22</span></font></b> Then a demon-possessed man <i>[who was]</i> blind and mute was brought to him. And he healed him so that the <i>[man who was]</i> mute could speak and see. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:23">23</span></font></b> And all the crowds were amazed and began saying, &ldquo;Perhaps this one is the Son of David!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:24">24</span></font></b> But the Pharisees, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;This man does not expel demons except by Beelzebul the ruler of demons!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:25">25</span></font></b> But knowing their thoughts, he said to them, &ldquo;Every kingdom divided against itself is laid waste, and every city or household divided against itself will not stand. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:26">26</span></font></b> And if Satan expels Satan, he is divided against himself. How then will his kingdom stand? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:27">27</span></font></b> And if I expel demons by Beelzebul, by whom do your sons expel <i>[them]</i>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> For this <i>[reason]</i> they will be your judges! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:28">28</span></font></b> But if I expel demons by the Spirit of God, then the kingdom of God has come upon you! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:29">29</span></font></b> Or how can someone enter into the house of a strong <i>[man]</i> and steal his property, unless he first ties up the strong <i>[man]</i>? And then he can thoroughly plunder his house. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:30">30</span></font></b> The one who is not with me is against me, and the one who does not gather with me scatters. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:31">31</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i> I tell you, every sin and blasphemy will be forgiven people, but the blasphemy against the Spirit will not be forgiven! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:32">32</span></font></b> And whoever speaks a word against the Son of Man, it will be forgiven him. But whoever speaks against the Holy Spirit, it will not be forgiven him either in this age or in the coming one! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:33">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:33">33</span></font></b> &ldquo;Either make the tree good and its fruit <i>[is]</i> good, or make the tree bad and its fruit <i>[is]</i> bad, for the tree is known by its fruit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:34">34</span></font></b> Offspring of vipers! How are you able to say good things <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;are&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are evil? For from the abundance of the heart the mouth speaks. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:35">35</span></font></b> The good person from his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> good treasury brings out good <i>[things]</i>, and the evil person from his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> evil treasury brings out evil <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:36">36</span></font></b> But I tell you that every worthless word that they speak, people will give an account for it on the day of judgment! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:37">37</span></font></b> For by your words you will be vindicated, and by your words you will be condemned.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:38">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:38">38</span></font></b> Then some of the scribes and Pharisees answered him saying, &ldquo;Teacher, we want to see a sign from you!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:39">39</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;An evil and adulterous generation desires a sign, and no sign will be given to it except the sign of the prophet Jonah! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:40">40</span></font></b> For just as Jonah was in the belly of the huge fish three days and three nights, so the Son of Man will be in the heart of the earth three days and three nights. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:41">41</span></font></b> The people of Nineveh will stand up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, because they repented at the proclamation of Jonah, and behold, <i>[something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;something&rdquo; is supplied in the translation because the adjective is neuter gender."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> greater than Jonah <i>[is]</i> here! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:42">42</span></font></b> The queen of the south will rise up at the judgment with this generation and condemn it, because she came from the ends of the earth to hear the wisdom of Solomon, and behold, <i>[something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;something&rdquo; is supplied in the translation because the adjective is neuter gender."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> greater than Solomon <i>[is]</i> here! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:43">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:43">43</span></font></b> &ldquo;Now whenever an unclean spirit has gone out of a person, it travels through waterless places searching for rest, and does not find <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:44">44</span></font></b> Then it says, &apos;I will return to my house from which I came out.&apos; And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrives&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arrives it finds <i>[the house]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> unoccupied and swept and put in order. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:45">45</span></font></b> Then it goes and brings along with itself seven other spirits more evil than itself, and <i>[they]</i> go in <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go in&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> live there. And the last <i>[state]</i> of that person becomes worse than the first. So it will be for this evil generation also!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="12:46">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:46">46</span></font></b> And<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;And.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was still speaking to the crowds, behold, his mother and brothers were standing there outside, desiring to speak to him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:47">47</span></font></b> And someone told him, &ldquo;Behold, your mother and your brothers are standing there outside desiring to speak to you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:48">48</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to the one who told him, &ldquo;Who is my mother, and who are my brothers?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:49">49</span></font></b> And stretching out his hand toward his disciples, he said, &ldquo;Behold my mother and my brothers! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="12:50">50</span></font></b> For whoever does the will of my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven, he is my brother and sister and mother.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:1">13:1</span></font></b> On that day Jesus went out of the house <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was sitting by the sea.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, the Sea of Galilee."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:2">2</span></font></b> And large crowds gathered close around him, so that he got into a boat to sit down, and all the crowd was standing on the shore. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:3">3</span></font></b> And he spoke many <i>[things]</i> to them in parables, saying, &ldquo;Behold, the sower went out to sow, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:4">4</span></font></b> and while he was sowing, <u>some seed</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;some of which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fell on the side of the path, and the birds came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> devoured it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:5">5</span></font></b> And other <i>[seed]</i> fell on the rocky ground, where it did not have much soil, and it sprang up at once because it did not have <i>[any]</i> depth of soil. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:6">6</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;rose&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the sun rose it was scorched, and because it did not have <i>[enough]</i> root, it withered. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:7">7</span></font></b> And other <i>[seed]</i> fell among the thorn plants, and the thorn plants came up and choked it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:8">8</span></font></b> But other <i>[seed]</i> fell on the good soil and produced grain,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;fruit,&rdquo; describing here the grain harvested from the healthy plants; in contemporary English this would more naturally be expressed by terms like &ldquo;grain&rdquo; or &ldquo;crop.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this one a hundred <i>[times as much]</i> and this one sixty and this one thirty. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:9">9</span></font></b> The one who has ears, let him hear!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:10">10</span></font></b> And the disciples came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;<u>Why</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;because of what.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> do you speak to them in parables?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:11">11</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;To you it has been granted to know the mysteries of the kingdom of heaven, but to those <i>[people]</i> it has not been granted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:12">12</span></font></b> For whoever has, to him <i>[more]</i> will be given, and he will have an abundance. But whoever does not have, even what he has will be taken away from him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:13">13</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i> I speak to them in parables, because seeing they do not see, and hearing they do not hear, nor do they understand, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:14">14</span></font></b> and with reference to them the prophecy of Isaiah is fulfilled that says, &ldquo;<u>You will listen carefully</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with hearing you will hear.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will never understand, and <u>you will look closely</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;seeing you will see.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and will never perceive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:15">15</span></font></b> For the heart of this people has become dull, and with their ears they hear with difficulty, and they have shut their eyes, so that they would not see with their eyes and hear with their ears and understand with their heart and turn, and I would heal them.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 6:9-10."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:16">16</span></font></b> But your eyes <i>[are]</i> blessed because they see, and your ears because they hear. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:17">17</span></font></b> For truly I say to you that many prophets and righteous <i>[people]</i> longed to see what you see, and did not see <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and to hear what you hear, and did not hear <i>[it]</i>!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:18">18</span></font></b> &ldquo;You, therefore, listen to the parable of the sower: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:19">19</span></font></b> <i>[When]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;hears&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> anyone hears the word about the kingdom and does not understand <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the evil one comes and snatches away what was sown in his heart. This is what was sown on the side of the path. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:20">20</span></font></b> And what was sown on the rocky ground--this is the one who hears the word and immediately receives it with joy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:21">21</span></font></b> But he does not have a root in himself, but <u>lasts only a little while</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is temporary.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;happens&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> affliction or persecution happens because of the word, immediately he falls away. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:22">22</span></font></b> And what was sown into the thorn plants--this is the one who hears the word, and the anxiety of this world<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;of the world.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the deceitfulness of wealth choke the word and it becomes unproductive. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:23">23</span></font></b> But what was sown on the good soil--this is the one who hears the word and understands <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who indeed bears fruit and produces, this one a hundred <i>[times as much]</i>, and this one sixty, and this one thirty.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:24">24</span></font></b> He put before them another parable, saying, &ldquo;The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a man who sowed good seed in his field. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:25">25</span></font></b> But while his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> people were sleeping, his enemy came and sowed darnel<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A weed that looks similar to wheat but has poisonous seeds."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the midst of the wheat and went away. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:26">26</span></font></b> So when the <u>wheat</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;grass,&rdquo; &ldquo;hay,&rdquo; but in this context referring to the good plants as opposed to the weeds."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sprouted and yielded grain, then the darnel appeared also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:27">27</span></font></b> So the slaves of the master of the house came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &apos;Master, did you not sow good seed in your field? How then does it have darnel?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:28">28</span></font></b> And he said to them, &apos;An enemy has done this!&apos; So the slaves said to him, &apos;Then do you want us to go <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as an English infinitive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gather them?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:29">29</span></font></b> But he said, &ldquo;No, lest <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;gather&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gather the darnel you uproot the wheat together with it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:30">30</span></font></b> Let both grow together until the harvest, and at the season of the harvest I will tell the reapers, &ldquo;First gather the darnel and tie it into bundles to burn them, but gather the wheat into my storehouse.&rdquo; &apos;&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:31">31</span></font></b> He put before them another parable, saying, &ldquo;The kingdom of heaven is like a mustard seed that a man took <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sowed in his field. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:32">32</span></font></b> <u>It</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;which,&rdquo; but a new sentence is started here in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> is the smallest of all the seeds, but when it is grown it is larger than the garden herbs and becomes a tree, so that the birds of the sky come and nest in its branches.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:33">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:33">33</span></font></b> He told them another parable: &ldquo;The kingdom of heaven is like yeast that a woman took <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put into three measures of wheat flour until the whole <i>[batch]</i> was leavened.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:34">34</span></font></b> Jesus spoke all these <i>[things]</i> to the crowds in parables, and he was saying nothing to them without a parable, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:35">35</span></font></b> in order that what was spoken through the prophet would be fulfilled, who said, &ldquo;I will open my mouth in parables; I will proclaim what has been hidden since the creation.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 78:2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;since the creation of the world.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:36">36</span></font></b> Then he left the crowds <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;left&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came into the house, and his disciples came to him saying, &ldquo;Explain the parable of the darnel in the field to us.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:37">37</span></font></b> So he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;The one who sows the good seed is the Son of Man, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:38">38</span></font></b> and the field is the world. And the good seed--these are the sons of the kingdom, but the darnel are the sons of the evil one. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:39">39</span></font></b> And the enemy who sowed them is the devil, and the harvest is the end of the age, and the reapers are angels. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:40">40</span></font></b> Thus just as the darnel is gathered and burned<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;burned up.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with fire, so it will be at the end of the age. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:41">41</span></font></b> The Son of Man will send out his angels and they will gather out of his kingdom all the causes of sin and those who do lawless deeds, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:42">42</span></font></b> and throw them into the fiery furnace.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Dan 3:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:43">43</span></font></b> Then the righteous will shine like the sun in the kingdom of their Father.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Dan 12:3."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> The one who has ears, let him hear! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:44">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:44">44</span></font></b> &ldquo;The kingdom of heaven is like treasure hidden in a field, that a man found <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> concealed, and in his joy he goes and sells everything that he has and buys that field. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:45">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:45">45</span></font></b> &ldquo;Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a merchant searching for fine pearls. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:46">46</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;found&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found one very valuable pearl, he went <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sold everything that he possessed and purchased it. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:47">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:47">47</span></font></b> &ldquo;Again, the kingdom of heaven is like a dragnet that was thrown into the sea and gathered <i>[fish]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of every kind, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:48">48</span></font></b> which when it was filled they pulled to shore and sat down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> collected the good <i>[fish]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the word &ldquo;<i>[fish]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> into containers, but the bad they threw out. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:49">49</span></font></b> Thus it will be at the end of the age. The angels will go out and separate the evil from among the righteous <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:50">50</span></font></b> and throw them into the fiery furnace.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Dan 3:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:51">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:51">51</span></font></b> &ldquo;Have you understood all these <i>[things]</i>?&rdquo; They said to him, &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:52">52</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;For this <i>[reason]</i> every scribe who has been trained for the kingdom of heaven is like the master of the house who brings out of his storeroom new <i>[things]</i> and old <i>[things]</i>.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="13:53">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:53">53</span></font></b> And it happened that when Jesus had finished these parables he went away from there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:54">54</span></font></b> And he came to his hometown <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to teach<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to teach&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them in their synagogue, so that they were amazed and said, &ldquo;From where did this man <i>[get]</i> this wisdom and these miracles? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:55">55</span></font></b> Is not this one the son of the carpenter? Is not his mother called Mary and his brothers James and Joseph and Simon and Judas? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:56">56</span></font></b> And are not all his sisters with us? From where then did this man <i>[get]</i> all these <i>[things]</i>?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:57">57</span></font></b> And they were offended by him. But Jesus said to them, &ldquo;A prophet is not without honor except in his <i>[own]</i> hometown and in his <i>[own]</i> household.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="13:58">58</span></font></b> And he did not perform many miracles in that place because of their unbelief. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:1">14:1</span></font></b> At that time Herod the tetrarch heard the report about Jesus <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:2">2</span></font></b> and he said to his servants, &ldquo;This is John the Baptist! He has been raised from the dead, and for this <i>[reason]</i> miraculous powers are at work in him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:3">3</span></font></b> For Herod, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arresting&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> arresting John, bound him and put <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in prison on account of Herodias, the wife of his brother Philip, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:4">4</span></font></b> because John had been saying to him, &ldquo;It is not permitted for you to have her.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[although he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to kill him, he feared the crowd, because they looked upon him as a prophet. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:6">6</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;took place&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Herod&apos;s birthday celebration took place, the daughter of Herodias danced in the midst <i>[of them]</i> and pleased Herod. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:7">7</span></font></b> Therefore he promised with an oath to give her whatever she asked. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:8">8</span></font></b> And coached by her mother, she said, &ldquo;Give me the head of John the Baptist here on a platter!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was distressed&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the king was distressed, because of his oaths and his <u>dinner guests</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those reclining at table with.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he commanded <i>[the request]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to be granted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:10">10</span></font></b> And he sent <i>[orders]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had John beheaded in the prison, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:11">11</span></font></b> and his head was brought on a platter and given to the girl, and she brought <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to her mother. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:12">12</span></font></b> And his disciples came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took away the corpse and buried it, and went <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> told Jesus. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:13">13</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he withdrew from there in a boat to an isolated place by himself. And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the crowds heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they followed him by land from the towns. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;got out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> got out, he saw the large crowd and had compassion on them and healed their sick. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:15">15</span></font></b> Now <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was evening, the disciples came to him saying, &ldquo;The place is desolate and the hour <u>is late</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;has passed away.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Release the crowds so that they can go away into the villages <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> purchase food for themselves.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:16">16</span></font></b> But Jesus said to them, &ldquo;They do not <u>need</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;have need.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to go away. You give them <i>[something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to eat.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:17">17</span></font></b> And they said to him, &ldquo;We do not have <i>[anything]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> here except five loaves and two fish.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:18">18</span></font></b> So he said, &ldquo;Bring them here to me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:19">19</span></font></b> And he commanded the crowds to recline for a meal on the grass. Taking the five loaves and the two fish <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; has been supplied in the English translation for stylistic reasons."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> looking up to heaven, he gave thanks. And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;breaking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> breaking <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he gave the loaves to the disciples, and the disciples <i>[gave them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="&ldquo;<i>[gave them]</i>&rdquo; is an implied repetition of the earlier verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the crowds. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:20">20</span></font></b> And they all ate and were satisfied, and they picked up what was left over of the broken pieces, twelve baskets full. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:21">21</span></font></b> Now those who ate were about five thousand men, in addition to women and children. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:22">22</span></font></b> And immediately he made the disciples get into the boat and go ahead of him to the other side, while he sent away the crowds. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;sent away&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sent away the crowds, he went up on the mountain by himself to pray. So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> evening came, he was there alone. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:24">24</span></font></b> But the boat was already many stadia distant from the land, being beaten by the waves, because the wind was against <i>[it]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:25">25</span></font></b> And in the fourth watch of the night he came to them, walking on the sea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:26">26</span></font></b> But the disciples, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw him walking on the sea, were terrified, saying, &ldquo;It is a ghost!&rdquo; and they cried out in fear. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:27">27</span></font></b> But immediately Jesus spoke to them, saying, &ldquo;Have courage, I am <i>[he]</i>! Do not be afraid!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:28">28</span></font></b> And Peter answered him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Lord, if <u>it is you</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;you are&rdquo; <i>[he]</i>."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> command me to come to you on the water!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:29">29</span></font></b> So he said, &ldquo;Come!&rdquo; And getting out of the boat, Peter walked on the water and came toward Jesus. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:30">30</span></font></b> But <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the strong wind, he was afraid. And beginning to sink, he cried out, saying, &ldquo;Lord, save me!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:31">31</span></font></b> And immediately Jesus extended his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;extended&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> caught him and said to him, &ldquo;<i>[You]</i> of little faith! Why did you doubt?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:32">32</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;got&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they got into the boat, the wind abated. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:33">33</span></font></b> So those in the boat worshiped him, saying, &ldquo;Truly you are the Son of God!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="14:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:34">34</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had crossed over&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had crossed over, they came to land at Gennesaret. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:35">35</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;recognized&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the men of that place recognized him, they sent <i>[word]</i> into that whole surrounding region, and they brought to him all those <u>who were sick</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;having badly.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="14:36">36</span></font></b> And they were imploring him that they might only touch the edge<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;tassel.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of his cloak, and all those who touched <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were cured. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:1">15:1</span></font></b> Then Pharisees and scribes came to Jesus from Jerusalem, saying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:2">2</span></font></b> &ldquo;Why do your disciples break the tradition of the elders? For they do not wash their hands when they eat <u>a meal</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;bread.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:3">3</span></font></b> So he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Why do you also break the commandment of God because of your tradition? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:4">4</span></font></b> For God said, &apos;Honor your<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father and your<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mother,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 20:12; Deut 5:16."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and &apos;The one who speaks evil of father or mother <u>must certainly die</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;let him die the death.&rdquo;">.<font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 21:17; Lev 20:9."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:5">5</span></font></b> But you say, &apos;Whoever says to his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father or his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mother, &ldquo;Whatever <u>benefit you would have received</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;you would have been benefited.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from me <i>[is]</i> a gift <i>[to God]</i>,&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:6">6</span></font></b> need not honor his father,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Most later manuscripts add &ldquo;or his mother.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and you make void the word of God for the sake of your tradition. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:7">7</span></font></b> Hypocrites! Isaiah correctly prophesied about you saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:8">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:8">8</span></font></b> &apos;This people honors me with their<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lips, but their heart is far, far away from me, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:9">9</span></font></b> and they worship me in vain, teaching <i>[as]</i> doctrines the commandments of men.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 29:13."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:10">10</span></font></b> And summoning the crowd, he said to them, &ldquo;Hear and understand: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:11">11</span></font></b> It is not what goes into the mouth that defiles a person, but what comes out of the mouth--this defiles a person.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:12">12</span></font></b> Then the disciples came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Do you know that the Pharisees were offended <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard this saying?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:13">13</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Every plant that my heavenly Father did not plant will be uprooted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:14">14</span></font></b> Let<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Depart from.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them! They are blind guides of the blind. And if the blind guide the blind, both will fall into a pit.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:15">15</span></font></b> But Peter answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Explain this parable to us.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:16">16</span></font></b> But he said, &ldquo;Are you also still without understanding? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:17">17</span></font></b> Do you not understand that everything that enters into the mouth goes into the stomach and is evacuated into the latrine? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:18">18</span></font></b> But the things that come out of the mouth come from the heart, and these defile the person. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:19">19</span></font></b> For from the heart come evil plans, murder, adultery, sexual immorality, theft, false witness, abusive speech. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:20">20</span></font></b> These are the things that defile a person. But eating with unwashed hands does not defile a person!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:21">21</span></font></b> And departing from there, Jesus went away to the region of Tyre and Sidon. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:22">22</span></font></b> And behold, a Canaanite woman from that district came <i>[and]</i> cried out, saying, &ldquo;Have mercy on me, Lord, Son of David! My daughter <i>[is]</i> severely possessed by a demon!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:23">23</span></font></b> But he did not answer her a word. And his disciples came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> asked him, saying, &ldquo;Send her away, because she is crying out after us!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:24">24</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;I was not sent except to the lost sheep of the house of Israel.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:25">25</span></font></b> But she came <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knelt down before him, saying, &ldquo;Lord, help me!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:26">26</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It is not right to take the children&apos;s bread and throw <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the dogs!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:27">27</span></font></b> So she said, &ldquo;Yes, Lord, for even the dogs eat the crumbs that fall from their master&apos;s table.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:28">28</span></font></b> Then Jesus answered <i>[and]</i> said to her, &ldquo;O woman, your faith <i>[is]</i> great! Let it be done for you as you want.&rdquo; And her daughter was healed from that hour. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:29">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:29">29</span></font></b> And departing from there, Jesus went along the Sea of Galilee, and he went up on the mountain <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was sitting there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:30">30</span></font></b> And large crowds came to him, having with them <i>[the]</i> mute, blind, lame, crippled,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;<i>[the]</i> lame, blind, crippled, mute.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and many others, and they put them down at his feet, and he healed them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:31">31</span></font></b> So then the crowd was astonished <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the mute speaking, the crippled healthy, and the lame walking, and the blind seeing, and they praised the God of Israel. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="15:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:32">32</span></font></b> And Jesus summoned his disciples <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;I have compassion on the crowd, because they have remained with me three days already and do not have anything to eat, and I do not want to send them away hungry lest they give out on the way.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:33">33</span></font></b> And the disciples said to him, &ldquo;Where in <i>[this]</i> desolate place <u>can we get</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for us.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so much bread that such a great crowd could be satisfied?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:34">34</span></font></b> And Jesus said to them, &ldquo;How many loaves do you have?&rdquo; So they said, &ldquo;Seven, and a few little fish.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:35">35</span></font></b> And commanding the crowd to recline for a meal on the ground, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:36">36</span></font></b> he took the seven loaves and the fish and <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had given thanks&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had given thanks, he broke <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and began giving<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began giving&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the disciples, and the disciples <i>[gave them]</i> to the crowds. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:37">37</span></font></b> And they all ate and were satisfied, and they picked up what was left over of the broken pieces, seven baskets full. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:38">38</span></font></b> Now those who ate were four thousand men, in addition to women and children. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="15:39">39</span></font></b> And <i>[after he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had given thanks&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sent away the crowds, he got into the boat and went to the region of Magadan. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:1">16:1</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Pharisees and Sadducees came to test <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they asked him to show them a sign from heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:2">2</span></font></b> So he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;<i>[When]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;comes&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> evening comes you say, &apos;<i>[It will be]</i> fair weather because the sky is red,&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:3">3</span></font></b> and early in the morning, &apos;Today <i>[it will be]</i> stormy weather, because the sky is red <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied in the translation because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> darkening.&apos; You know how to evaluate correctly the appearance of the sky, but you are not able <i>[to evaluate]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[to evaluate]</i>&rdquo; is an implied repetition of the verb earlier in the verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the signs of the times. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:4">4</span></font></b> An evil and adulterous generation seeks for a sign, and a sign will not be given to it except the sign of Jonah!&rdquo; And he left them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;left&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went away. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples arrived at the other side,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="That is, the other side of the Sea of Galilee."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had forgotten to take bread. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:6">6</span></font></b> And Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Watch out for and beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:7">7</span></font></b> So they were discussing <i>[this]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> among themselves, saying, &ldquo;<i>[It is]</i> because we did not take bread.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:8">8</span></font></b> But knowing <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus said, &ldquo;Why are you discussing among yourselves that you did not take bread,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;you do not have bread.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[you]</i> of little faith? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:9">9</span></font></b> Do you not yet understand or do you not remember the five loaves for the five thousand, and how many baskets you took up? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:10">10</span></font></b> Or the seven loaves for the four thousand and how many baskets you took up? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:11">11</span></font></b> How do you not understand that I did not speak to you about bread? But beware of the leaven of the Pharisees and Sadducees!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:12">12</span></font></b> Then they understood that he did not say to beware of the leaven of bread, but of the teaching of the Pharisees and Sadducees. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:13">13</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus came to the region of Caesarea <u>Philippi</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;of Philip.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he began asking<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began asking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his disciples, saying, &ldquo;Who do people say <i>[that]</i> the Son of Man is?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:14">14</span></font></b> And they said, <u>Some</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;those on the one hand.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[say]</i> John the Baptist, but others Elijah, and others Jeremiah or one of the prophets.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:15">15</span></font></b> He said to them, &ldquo;But who do you say <i>[that]</i> I am?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:16">16</span></font></b> And Simon Peter answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You are the Christ, the Son of the living God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:17">17</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Blessed are you, Simon son of Jonah, because flesh and blood did not reveal <i>[this]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you, but my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:18">18</span></font></b> And I also say to you that you are Peter, and on this rock I will build my church, and the gates of Hades will not overpower it! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:19">19</span></font></b> I will give you the keys of the kingdom of heaven, and whatever you bind on earth will be bound<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;will have been bound.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in heaven, and whatever you release on earth will be released<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;will have been released.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in heaven.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:20">20</span></font></b> Then he commanded the disciples that they should tell no one that he was the Christ. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:21">21</span></font></b> From that time <i>[on]</i> Jesus began to show his disciples that he must go to Jerusalem and suffer many <i>[things]</i> from the elders and chief priests and scribes, and be killed, and be raised on the third day. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:22">22</span></font></b> And Peter took him aside <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took ... aside&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to rebuke him, saying, <u>God forbid</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;merciful to you.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Lord! This will never happen to you!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:23">23</span></font></b> But he turned around <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;turned around&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Peter, &ldquo;Get behind me, Satan! You are a cause for stumbling to me, because you are not intent on the things of God, but the things of people!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="16:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:24">24</span></font></b> Then Jesus said to his disciples, &ldquo;If anyone wants to come after me, let him deny himself and take up his cross and follow me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:25">25</span></font></b> For whoever wants to save his life will lose it, but whoever loses his life on account of me will find it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:26">26</span></font></b> For what will a person be benefited if he gains the whole world but forfeits his life? Or what will a person give in exchange for his life? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:27">27</span></font></b> For the Son of Man is going to come in the glory of his Father with his angels, and at that time he will reward each one according to <u>what he has done</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;his activity.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="16:28">28</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, that there are some of those standing here who will never experience death until they see the Son of Man coming in his kingdom.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:1">17:1</span></font></b> And after six days Jesus took along Peter and James and John his brother, and led them up on a high mountain by themselves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:2">2</span></font></b> And he was transfigured before them, and his face shone like the sun, and his clothing became bright as the light. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:3">3</span></font></b> And behold, Moses and Elijah appeared to them, talking with him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:4">4</span></font></b> So Peter answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Jesus, &ldquo;Lord, it is good <i>[that]</i> we are here! If you want, I will make here three shelters, one for you and one for Moses and one for Elijah.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:5">5</span></font></b> <i>[While]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was still speaking, behold, a bright cloud overshadowed them, and behold, a voice from the cloud said, &ldquo;This is my beloved Son, with whom I am well pleased. Listen to him!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:6">6</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they fell down on their faces and were extremely frightened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:7">7</span></font></b> And Jesus came and touched them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;touched&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Get up and do not be afraid.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:8">8</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;lifted up&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> lifted up their eyes they saw no one except him--Jesus alone. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were coming down&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were coming down from the mountain, Jesus commanded them saying, &ldquo;Tell no one the vision until the Son of Man is raised from the dead.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:10">10</span></font></b> And the disciples asked him, saying, &ldquo;Then why do the scribes say that Elijah must come first?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:11">11</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Elijah indeed is coming, and will restore all <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:12">12</span></font></b> But I say to you that Elijah has already come, and they did not recognize him, but did with him whatever they wanted. In the <i>[same]</i> way also the Son of Man is going to suffer <i>[at]</i> their hands.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:13">13</span></font></b> Then the disciples understood that he had spoken to them about John the Baptist. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:14">14</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to the crowd, a man approached him, kneeling down before him <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:15">15</span></font></b> and saying, &ldquo;Lord, have mercy on my son, because he has seizures and suffers severely, for often he falls into the fire and often into the water. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:16">16</span></font></b> And I brought him to your disciples, and they were not able to heal him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:17">17</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;O unbelieving and perverse generation! <u>How long</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;until when.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> will I be with you? <u>How long</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;until when.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> must I put up with you? Bring him here to me!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:18">18</span></font></b> And Jesus rebuked him, and the demon came out of him and the boy was healed from that hour. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:19">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:19">19</span></font></b> Then the disciples approached Jesus privately <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, <u>Why</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for what.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were we not able to expel it?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:20">20</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Because of your little faith. For truly I say to you, if you have faith like a mustard seed, you will say to this mountain, &apos;Move from here <i>[to]</i> there,&apos; and it will move, and nothing will be impossible for you.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Most later Greek manuscripts add v. 21, &ldquo;But this kind does not go out except by prayer and fasting.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:22">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:22">22</span></font></b> Now <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were gathering&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were gathering in Galilee, Jesus said to them, &ldquo;The Son of Man is going to be betrayed into the hands of men,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or possibly &ldquo;of people,&rdquo; in a generic sense, although the reference here may be to the specific group responsible for Jesus&apos; arrest, where it is unlikely women were present."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:23">23</span></font></b> and they will kill him, and on the third day he will be raised.&rdquo; And they were extremely distressed. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="17:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:24">24</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they arrived in Capernaum, the ones who collected the double drachma <i>[tax]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This refers to the half-shekel annual tax paid by Jewish males to support the temple; over time the name of the coin commonly used to pay the tax came to be used for the tax itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came up to Peter and said, &ldquo;Does your teacher not pay the double drachma <i>[tax]</i>?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:25">25</span></font></b> He said, &ldquo;Yes.&rdquo; And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came into the house, Jesus spoke to him first, saying, &ldquo;What do you think, Simon? From whom do the kings of the earth collect tolls or taxes--from their own sons, or from foreigners?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:26">26</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;said&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;From foreigners,&rdquo; Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Then the sons are free. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="17:27">27</span></font></b> But so that we do not give offense to them, go out to the sea, cast <i>[a line with]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[a line with]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a hook, and take the first fish that comes up. And <i>[when you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;open&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> open its mouth, you will find a four-drachma coin. Take that <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;take&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> give <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them for me and you.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:1">18:1</span></font></b> At that time the disciples came up to Jesus, saying, &ldquo;Who then is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:2">2</span></font></b> And calling a child <i>[to himself]</i>, he had him stand in their midst <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:3">3</span></font></b> and said, &ldquo;Truly I say to you, unless you turn around and become like young children, you will never enter into the kingdom of heaven! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:4">4</span></font></b> Therefore whoever humbles himself like this child, this person is the greatest in the kingdom of heaven, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:5">5</span></font></b> and whoever welcomes one child such as this in my name welcomes me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:6">6</span></font></b> But whoever causes one of these little ones who believe in me to sin, it would be better for him that <u>a large millstone</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;a millstone of a donkey.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> be hung on<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;around.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his neck and he be drowned in the depths of the sea. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:7">7</span></font></b> Woe to the world because of causes for stumbling, for <i>[it is]</i> a necessity <i>[that]</i> causes for stumbling come; nevertheless, woe to the person through whom the cause for stumbling comes. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:8">8</span></font></b> And if your hand or your foot causes you to sin, cut it off and throw <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from you! It is better for you to enter into life crippled or lame than, having two hands or two feet, to be thrown into the eternal fire! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:9">9</span></font></b> And if your eye causes you to sin, tear it out and throw <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from you! It is better for you to enter into life one-eyed than, having two eyes, to be thrown into fiery hell! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:10">10</span></font></b> &ldquo;See to it that you do not despise one of these little ones, for I tell you that their angels in heaven constantly see the face of my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Many later Greek manuscripts include vs. 11, &ldquo;For the Son of Man came to save those who are lost.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:12">12</span></font></b> What do you think? If <u>a certain man has</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;there are to a certain man.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a hundred sheep, and one of them wanders away, will he not leave the ninety-nine on the hills and go <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> look for the one that wandered away? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:13">13</span></font></b> And if he happens to find it, truly I say to you that he rejoices over it more than over the ninety-nine that did not wander away. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:14">14</span></font></b> In the <i>[same]</i> way it is not the will <u>of</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the presence of.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> your Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven that one of these little ones perish. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:15">15</span></font></b> &ldquo;Now if your brother sins against you, go correct him between you and him alone. If he listens to you, you have gained your brother. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:16">16</span></font></b> But if he does not listen, take with you in addition one or two <i>[others]</i>, so that by <u>the testimony</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the mouth.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of two or three witnesses every matter may be established. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:17">17</span></font></b> And if he refuses to listen to them, tell <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the church. But if he refuses to listen to the church also, let him be to you as a Gentile and a tax collector. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:18">18</span></font></b> &ldquo;Truly I say to you, whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven, and whatever you release on earth will be released in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:19">19</span></font></b> Again, truly I say to you that if two of you agree on earth about any matter that they ask, it will be done for them from my Father <i>[who is]</i> in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:20">20</span></font></b> For where two or three are gathered in my name, I am there in the midst of them.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:21">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:21">21</span></font></b> Then Peter came up to him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;Then Peter came up <i>[and]</i> said to him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Lord, how many times will my brother sin against me and I will forgive him? Up to seven times?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:22">22</span></font></b> Jesus said to him, &ldquo;I do not say to you up to seven times, but up to seventy times seven!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;seventy-seven times.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="18:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:23">23</span></font></b> &ldquo;For this <i>[reason]</i> the kingdom of heaven may be compared to a man--a king--who wanted to settle accounts with his slaves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;began&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he began to settle <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> someone was brought to him who owed ten thousand talents. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:25">25</span></font></b> And <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;have&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he did not have <i>[enough]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to repay <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the master ordered him to be sold, and his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wife and his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> children and everything that he had, and to be repaid. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:26">26</span></font></b> Then the slave threw himself to the ground <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;threw himself to the ground&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to do obeisance to him, saying, &apos;Be patient with me, and I will pay back everything to you!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:27">27</span></font></b> So the master of that slave, <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had compassion&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had compassion, released him and forgave him the loan. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:28">28</span></font></b> But that slave went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found one of his fellow slaves who owed him a hundred denarii, and taking hold of him, he began to choke <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, &apos;Pay back everything that you owe!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:29">29</span></font></b> Then his fellow slave threw himself to the ground <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;threw himself to the ground&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> began to implore<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to implore&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> him, saying, &apos;Be patient with me and I will repay you!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:30">30</span></font></b> But he did not want to, but rather he went <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> threw him into prison until he would repay what was owed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:31">31</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> his fellow slaves saw what had happened, they were extremely distressed, and went <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported to their master everything that had happened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:32">32</span></font></b> Then his master summoned him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;summoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &apos;Wicked slave! I forgave you all that debt because you implored me! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:33">33</span></font></b> Should you not also have shown mercy to your fellow slave as I also showed mercy to you?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:34">34</span></font></b> And <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was angry&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was angry, his master handed him over to the merciless jailers<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;torturers.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> until he would repay everything that was owed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="18:35">35</span></font></b> So also my heavenly Father will do to you, unless each of you forgives his brother from your hearts!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:1">19:1</span></font></b> And it happened that when Jesus had finished these statements, he went away from Galilee and came into the region of Judea on the other side of the Jordan. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:2">2</span></font></b> And large crowds followed him, and he healed them there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:3">3</span></font></b> And Pharisees came up to him <i>[in order to]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[in order to]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;test&rdquo;) which is understood as purpose."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> test him, and asked<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;asked&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> if it was permitted for a man to divorce his wife for any cause. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:4">4</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Have you not read that the one who created <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> from the beginning made them male and female <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:5">5</span></font></b> and said, &apos;On account of this a man will leave his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father and his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mother and will be joined to his wife, and the two will become one flesh&apos;?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Gen 2:24."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:6">6</span></font></b> So then, they are no longer two but one flesh. Therefore what God has joined together, man must not separate.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:7">7</span></font></b> They said to him, &ldquo;Why then did Moses command <i>[us]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to give a document--a certificate of divorce--and to divorce her?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:8">8</span></font></b> He said to them, &ldquo;Moses, with reference to your hardness of heart, permitted you to divorce your wives, but from the beginning it was not like this. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:9">9</span></font></b> Now I say to you that whoever divorces his wife, except on the basis of sexual immorality, and marries another commits adultery, and whoever marries her who is divorced commits adultery.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;and whoever marries her who is divorced commits adultery.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:10">10</span></font></b> The disciples<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;His disciples.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;If this is the case of a man with his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wife, it would be better not to marry!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:11">11</span></font></b> But he said to them, &ldquo;Not everyone can accept this saying but <i>[those]</i> to whom it has been given. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:12">12</span></font></b> For there are eunuchs who were born as such from <i>[their]</i> mother&apos;s womb, and there are eunuchs who were made eunuchs by people, and there are eunuchs who have made themselves <i>[eunuchs]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An understood repetition of the term from earlier in the verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for the sake of the kingdom of heaven. The one who is able to accept <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> let him accept <i>[it]</i>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:13">13</span></font></b> Then children were brought to him so that he could lay his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on them and pray, but the disciples rebuked them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:14">14</span></font></b> But Jesus said, &ldquo;Allow the children, and do not forbid them to come to me, <u>for to such belongs</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for of such is.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the kingdom of heaven.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:15">15</span></font></b> And he laid his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands on them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;laid&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> traveled on from there. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:16">16</span></font></b> And behold, someone came up to him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Teacher, what good <i>[thing]</i> must I do so that I will have eternal life?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:17">17</span></font></b> And he said to him, &ldquo;Why are you asking me about <i>[what is]</i> good? There is one <i>[who is]</i> good. But if you want to enter into life, keep the commandments!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:18">18</span></font></b> He said to him, &ldquo;Which <i>[ones]</i>?&rdquo; And Jesus said, &ldquo;Do not commit murder, do not commit adultery, do not steal, do not give false testimony, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:19">19</span></font></b> honor your<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father and your<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> mother, and love your neighbor as yourself.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:20">20</span></font></b> The young man said to him, &ldquo;All these I have observed. What do I still lack?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:21">21</span></font></b> Jesus said to him, &ldquo;If you want to be perfect, go, sell your possessions and give <i>[the proceeds]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the poor--and you will have treasure in heaven--and come, follow me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:22">22</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the young man heard the statement, he went away sorrowful, because he was one who had many possessions. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="19:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:23">23</span></font></b> And Jesus said to his disciples, &ldquo;Truly I say to you that with difficulty a rich person will enter into the kingdom of heaven! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:24">24</span></font></b> And again I say to you, it is easier <i>[for]</i> a camel to go through the eye of a needle than a rich person into<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;to enter into.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the kingdom of God.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:25">25</span></font></b> So <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were extremely amazed, saying, &ldquo;Then who can be saved?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:26">26</span></font></b> But Jesus looked at <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;looked at&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;With human beings this is impossible, but with God all <i>[things]</i> <i>[are]</i> possible.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:27">27</span></font></b> Then Peter answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Behold, we have left everything and followed you. What then will there be for us?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:28">28</span></font></b> And Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Truly I say to you that in the renewal <i>[of the world]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;of the world&rdquo; are supplied as a clarification of &ldquo;renewal.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> when the Son of Man sits on his glorious throne, you who have followed me--you also will sit on twelve thrones judging the twelve tribes of Israel. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:29">29</span></font></b> And everyone who has left houses or brothers or sisters or father or mother or wife<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;or wife.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> or children or fields on account of my name will receive a hundred times as much, and will inherit eternal life. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="19:30">30</span></font></b> But many <i>[who are]</i> first will be last, and the last first. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:1">20:1</span></font></b> &ldquo;For the kingdom of heaven is like a man--the master of the house--who went out early in the morning to hire workers for his vineyard. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;coming to an agreement&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> coming to an agreement with the workers for a denarius per day, he sent them into his vineyard. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:3">3</span></font></b> And going out about the third hour, he saw others standing idle in the marketplace. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:4">4</span></font></b> And to those <i>[people]</i> he said, &apos;You also go into the vineyard, and I will give you whatever is right.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:5">5</span></font></b> So they went. Going out<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;And going out.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> again about the sixth and ninth hour he did the same <i>[thing]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:6">6</span></font></b> And about the eleventh <i>[hour]</i> he went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found others standing <i>[there]</i> and said to them, &apos;Why are you standing here the whole day unemployed?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:7">7</span></font></b> They said to him, &apos;Because no one hired us.&apos; He said to them, &apos;You go also into the vineyard.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:8">8</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> evening came, the owner of the vineyard said to his manager, &apos;Call the workers and pay them their<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wages, beginning from the last up to the first.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:9">9</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i> the ones <i>[hired]</i> about the eleventh hour came, they received a denarius apiece. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the first came, they thought that they would receive more, and they also received a denarius apiece. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;received&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> received <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they began to complain<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to complain&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> against the master of the house, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:12">12</span></font></b> saying, &apos;These last <i>[people]</i> worked one hour and you made them equal to us who have endured the burden of the day and the burning heat!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:13">13</span></font></b> But he answered one of them <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;Friend, I am not doing you wrong. Did you not come to an agreement with me for a denarius? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:14">14</span></font></b> Take <i>[what is]</i> yours and go! But I want to give to this last <i>[person]</i> <i>[the same]</i> as <i>[I gave]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[I gave]</i>&rdquo; are an implied repetition from the verb earlier in the verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to you also. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:15">15</span></font></b> Is it not<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;Or <i>[is it]</i> not.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> permitted for me to do whatever I want with <i>[what is]</i> mine? Or is your eye evil because I am generous?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:16">16</span></font></b> Thus the last will be first and the first last.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:17">17</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was going up&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus was going up to Jerusalem, he took the twelve disciples by themselves and said to them on the way, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:18">18</span></font></b> &ldquo;Behold, we are going up to Jerusalem, and the Son of Man will be handed over to the chief priests and scribes, and they will condemn him to death, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:19">19</span></font></b> and will hand him over to the Gentiles to mock <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and flog <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and crucify <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and on the third day he will be raised.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:20">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:20">20</span></font></b> Then the mother of the sons of Zebedee came up to him with her sons, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle (&ldquo;kneeling down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb in keeping with English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> kneeling down <i>[she]</i> asked<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;asked&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> something from him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:21">21</span></font></b> And he said to her, &ldquo;What do you want?&rdquo; She said to him, &ldquo;Say that these two sons of mine may sit one at your right hand and one at your left in your kingdom.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:22">22</span></font></b> But Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You do not know what you are asking! Are you able to drink the cup that I am about to drink?&rdquo; They said to him, &ldquo;We are able.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:23">23</span></font></b> He said to them, &ldquo;You will indeed drink my cup, but to sit at my right hand and at my left is not mine<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;this is not mine.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to grant, but <i>[is]</i> for those for whom it has been prepared by my Father.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:24">24</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the ten heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were indignant concerning the two brothers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:25">25</span></font></b> But Jesus called them to himself <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;called ... to himself&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You know that the rulers of the Gentiles lord it over them, and those in high positions exercise authority over them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:26">26</span></font></b> It will not be like this among you! But whoever wants to become great among you must be your servant, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:27">27</span></font></b> and whoever wants to be most prominent among you must be your slave-- <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:28">28</span></font></b> just as the Son of Man did not come to be served, but to serve, and to give his life <i>[as]</i> a ransom for many.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="20:29">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:29">29</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going out&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were going out of Jericho, a large crowd followed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:30">30</span></font></b> And behold, <i>[there were]</i> two blind men sitting beside the road. <i>[When they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard that Jesus was passing by, they called out, saying, &ldquo;Lord, have mercy on us,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;Have mercy on us, Lord.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Son of David!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:31">31</span></font></b> And the crowd rebuked them so that they would be quiet. But they called out all the more, saying, &ldquo;Lord, have mercy on us,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;Have mercy on us, Lord.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Son of David!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:32">32</span></font></b> And Jesus stopped,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;stopped&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> called them, and said, &ldquo;What do you want me to do for you?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:33">33</span></font></b> They said to him, &ldquo;Lord, that our eyes be opened!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="20:34">34</span></font></b> And having compassion, Jesus touched their eyes, and immediately they received <i>[their]</i> sight and followed him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:1">21:1</span></font></b> And when they drew near to Jerusalem and came to Bethphage at the Mount of Olives, then Jesus sent two disciples, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:2">2</span></font></b> saying to them, &ldquo;Go into the village before you, and right away you will find a donkey tied and a colt with her. Untie <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;untie&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> bring <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:3">3</span></font></b> And if anyone says anything to you, you will say, &apos;The Lord <u>needs them</u>,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;has need of them.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and he will send them at once.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:4">4</span></font></b> Now this took place so that what was spoken through the prophet would be fulfilled, saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:5">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:5">5</span></font></b> &ldquo;Say to the daughter of Zion, &apos;Behold, your king is coming to you, humble and mounted on a donkey, and<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;even.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on a colt, the foal of a pack animal.&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Zech 9:9."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:6">6</span></font></b> So the disciples went<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and did<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the participle (&ldquo;did&rdquo;) is translated as a finite verb because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> just as Jesus directed them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:7">7</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participles (&ldquo;went&rdquo; and &ldquo;did&rdquo; in the previous verse) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought the donkey and the colt and put their<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> cloaks on them, and he sat on them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:8">8</span></font></b> And a very large crowd spread their cloaks on the road, and others were cutting branches from the trees and spreading <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on the road. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:9">9</span></font></b> And the crowds who went ahead of him and the ones who followed were shouting, saying, &ldquo;Hosanna to the Son of David! Blessed <i>[is]</i> the one who comes in the name of the Lord!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 118:25-26."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Hosanna in the highest <i>[heaven]</i>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;heaven&rdquo; is understood."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:10">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:10">10</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;entered&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he entered into Jerusalem, the whole city was stirred up, saying, &ldquo;Who is this?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:11">11</span></font></b> And the crowds were saying, &ldquo;This is the prophet Jesus from Nazareth of Galilee!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:12">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:12">12</span></font></b> And Jesus entered the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and drove out all those who were selling and buying in the temple, and overturned the tables of the money changers and the chairs of those who were selling doves. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:13">13</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;It is written, &apos;My house will be called a house of prayer,&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 56:7."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> but you have made it a cave of robbers!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:14">14</span></font></b> And the blind and the lame came up to him in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and he healed them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:15">15</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the chief priests and the scribes saw the wonderful <i>[things]</i> that he did, and the children shouting in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and saying, &ldquo;Hosanna to the Son of David!&rdquo; they were indignant. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:16">16</span></font></b> And they said to him, &ldquo;Do you hear what these <i>[children]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[children]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> are saying?&rdquo; So Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Yes, have you never read, &apos;Out of the mouths of children and nursing babies you have prepared for yourself praise&apos;?&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 8:2."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:17">17</span></font></b> And leaving them, he went outside of the city to Bethany and spent the night there. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:18">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:18">18</span></font></b> Now early in the morning, <i>[as he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was returning&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was returning to the city, he was hungry. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:19">19</span></font></b> And seeing a single fig tree by the road, he went to it and found nothing on it except leaves only. And he said to it, &ldquo;May there be no more fruit from you <u>forever</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;to the age.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and the fig tree withered at once. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples were astonished, saying, &ldquo;How did the fig tree wither at once?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:21">21</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Truly I say to you, if you have faith and do not doubt, you will do not only <i>[what was done to]</i> the fig tree, but even if you say to this mountain, &apos;Be lifted up and thrown into the sea,&rdquo; it will happen! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:22">22</span></font></b> And whatever you ask in prayer, <i>[if you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[if]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;believe&rdquo;) which is understood as conditional."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> believe, you will receive.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:23">23</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;arrived&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he arrived at the temple, the chief priests and the elders of the people came up to him <i>[while he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was teaching&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was teaching, saying, &ldquo;By what authority are you doing these <i>[things]</i>? And who gave you this authority?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:24">24</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;I also will ask you one question. If you tell <i>[the answer]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to me, I also will tell you by what authority I am doing these <i>[things]</i>. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:25">25</span></font></b> From where was the baptism of John--from heaven or from men?&rdquo; And they began to discuss<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to discuss&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[this]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> among themselves, saying, &ldquo;If we say &apos;From heaven,&apos; he will say to us, &apos;Why then did you not believe him?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:26">26</span></font></b> But if we say, &apos;From men,&apos; we are afraid of the crowd, because they all look upon John as a prophet.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:27">27</span></font></b> And they answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Jesus, &ldquo;We do not know.&rdquo; And he said to them, &ldquo;Neither will I tell you by what authority I am doing these <i>[things]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:28">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:28">28</span></font></b> &ldquo;Now what do you think? A man had two sons. <i>[He]</i> approached<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;And he approached.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the first <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;Son, go work in the vineyard today.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:29">29</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;I do not want to!&apos; But later <i>[he]</i> changed his mind <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;changed his mind&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:30">30</span></font></b> And <i>[he]</i> approached the second<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;the other.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said the same <i>[thing]</i>. So he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;I <i>[will]</i>, sir,&apos; and he did not go. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:31">31</span></font></b> Which of the two did the will of <i>[his]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> father?&rdquo; They said, &ldquo;The first.&rdquo; Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Truly I say to you that the tax collectors and the prostitutes are going ahead of you into the kingdom of God! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:32">32</span></font></b> For John came to you in the way of righteousness and you did not believe him, but the tax collectors and the prostitutes did believe him. And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you saw <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you did not even change your minds later <i>[so as]</i> to believe in him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:33">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:33">33</span></font></b> &ldquo;Listen to another parable: There was a man--a master of a house--who planted a vineyard, and put a fence <i>[around]</i> it, and dug a winepress in it, and built a watchtower, and leased it to tenant farmers, and went on a journey. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:34">34</span></font></b> And when the season of fruit drew near, he sent his slaves to the tenant farmers to collect his fruit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:35">35</span></font></b> And the tenant farmers seized his slaves, <i>[one of]</i> whom they beat, and <i>[one of]</i> whom they killed, and <i>[one of]</i> whom they stoned. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:36">36</span></font></b> Again, he sent other slaves, more than the first <i>[ones]</i>, and they did the same <i>[thing]</i> to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:37">37</span></font></b> So finally he sent his son to them, saying, &apos;They will respect my son.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:38">38</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the tenant farmers saw the son, they said among themselves, &apos;This is the heir. Come, let us kill him and have his inheritance!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:39">39</span></font></b> And they seized him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;seized&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> threw <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out of the vineyard and killed <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:40">40</span></font></b> Now when the master of the vineyard arrives, what will he do to those tenant farmers?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:41">41</span></font></b> They said to him, &ldquo;He will destroy those evil <i>[men]</i> completely and lease the vineyard to other tenant farmers who will give him the fruits in their season.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:42">42</span></font></b> Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Have you never read in the scriptures, &apos;The stone which the builders rejected, this has become <u>the cornerstone</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the head of the corner.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> This came about from the Lord, and it is marvelous in our eyes&apos;?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 118:22-23."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="21:43">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:43">43</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i>, I tell you that the kingdom of God will be taken away from you and will be given to a people<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;nation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> who produce its fruits. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:44">44</span></font></b> And the one who falls on this stone will be broken to pieces, and <i>[the one]</i> on whom it falls--it will crush him!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:45">45</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the chief priests and the Pharisees heard his parables, they knew that he was speaking about them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="21:46">46</span></font></b> and <i>[although they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;wanted&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wanted to arrest him, they were afraid of the crowds, because they looked upon him as a prophet. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:1">22:1</span></font></b> And continuing, Jesus spoke to them again in parables, saying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:2">2</span></font></b> &ldquo;The kingdom of heaven may be compared to a man--a king--who gave a wedding celebration for his son. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:3">3</span></font></b> And he sent his slaves to summon those who had been invited to the wedding celebration, and they did not want to come. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:4">4</span></font></b> Again he sent other slaves, saying, &apos;Tell those who have been invited, &ldquo;Behold, I have prepared my dinner; my oxen and fattened <i>[cattle]</i> have been slaughtered, and everything <i>[is]</i> ready. Come to the wedding celebration!&rdquo; &apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:5">5</span></font></b> But they paid no attention <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;paid no attention&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went away--this one to his own field, that one to his business. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:6">6</span></font></b> And the others, seizing his slaves, mistreated <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and killed <i>[them]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:7">7</span></font></b> And the king was angry and sent his troops <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sent&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> destroyed those murderers and burned their city. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:8">8</span></font></b> Then he said to his slaves, &apos;The wedding celebration is ready, but those who had been invited were not worthy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:9">9</span></font></b> Therefore, go out to the <i>[places where]</i> the roads exit the city and invite to the wedding celebration as many <i>[people]</i> as you find.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:10">10</span></font></b> And those slaves went out into the roads <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gathered everyone whom they found, both evil and good, and the wedding celebration was filled <u>with dinner guests</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;with those reclining at table.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:11">11</span></font></b> But <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came in&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the king came in to see the <u>dinner guests</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;ones reclining at table.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he saw a man there not dressed <i>[in]</i> wedding clothes. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:12">12</span></font></b> And he said to him, &apos;Friend, how did you come in here, not having wedding clothes?&apos; But <u>he could say nothing</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;he was silent.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:13">13</span></font></b> Then the king said to the servants, &apos;Tie him up <u>hand and foot</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;feet and hands.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;tie&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> throw him into the outer darkness. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:14">14</span></font></b> For many are called but few <i>[are]</i> chosen.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:15">15</span></font></b> Then the Pharisees went <u>and consulted</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;took counsel.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so that they could entrap him with a statement. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:16">16</span></font></b> And they sent their disciples to him with the Herodians, saying, &ldquo;Teacher, we know that you are truthful and teach the way of God in truth, and <u>you do not care what anyone thinks</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;it is not a care to you concerning anyone.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <u>because you do not regard the opinion of people</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;because you do not look at the face of men.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:17">17</span></font></b> Therefore tell us what you think. Is it permitted to pay taxes to Caesar or not?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:18">18</span></font></b> But <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;knew&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knew their maliciousness, Jesus said, &ldquo;Hypocrites! Why are you testing me? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:19">19</span></font></b> Show me the coin for the tax!&rdquo; So they brought him a denarius. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:20">20</span></font></b> And he said to them, &ldquo;Whose image and inscription <i>[is]</i> this?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:21">21</span></font></b> They said to him, &ldquo;Caesar&apos;s.&rdquo; Then he said to them, &ldquo;Therefore give to Caesar the things of Caesar, and to God the things of God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:22">22</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were astonished, and they left him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;left&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went away. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:23">23</span></font></b> On that day Sadducees--who say there is no resurrection--came up to him and asked him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:24">24</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Teacher, Moses said if someone dies without having children, his brother is to marry his wife and <u>father</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;raise up.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> descendants for his brother. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:25">25</span></font></b> Now there were seven brothers with us. And the first died <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;getting married&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> getting married, and <i>[because he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;have&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did not have descendants, he left his wife to his brother. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:26">26</span></font></b> So also the second and the third, up to the seventh. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:27">27</span></font></b> And last of all the woman died. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:28">28</span></font></b> In the resurrection, therefore, whose wife of the seven will she be? For they all had her <i>[as wife]</i>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[as wife]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:29">29</span></font></b> But Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;You are mistaken, <i>[because]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;know&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you do not know the scriptures or the power of God! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:30">30</span></font></b> For in the resurrection they neither marry nor are given in marriage, but are like angels of God<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;of God.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in heaven. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:31">31</span></font></b> Now concerning the resurrection of the dead, have you not read what was spoken to you by God, who said, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:32">32</span></font></b> &ldquo;I am the God of Abraham and the God of Isaac and the God of Jacob&rdquo;?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Exod 3:6."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> He is not the God of the dead, but of the living!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:33">33</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the crowds heard <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were amazed at his teaching. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:34">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:34">34</span></font></b> Now <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Pharisees heard that he had silenced the Sadducees, they assembled at the same <i>[place]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;they assembled together.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:35">35</span></font></b> And one of them, a legal expert, put a question to <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to test him: <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:36">36</span></font></b> &ldquo;Teacher, which commandment <i>[is]</i> greatest in the law?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:37">37</span></font></b> And he said to him, &ldquo; &apos;You shall love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Deut 6:5."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:38">38</span></font></b> This is the greatest and first commandment. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:39">39</span></font></b> And the second <i>[is]</i> like it: &apos;You shall love your neighbor as yourself.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Lev 19:18."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:40">40</span></font></b> On these two commandments depend all the law and the prophets.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:41">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:41">41</span></font></b> Now <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;assembled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the Pharisees were assembled, Jesus asked them, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:42">42</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;What do you think about the Christ? Whose son is he?&rdquo; They said to him, &ldquo;David&apos;s.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:43">43</span></font></b> He said to them, &ldquo;How then does David, by the Spirit, call him &apos;Lord,&apos; saying, </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:44">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:44">44</span></font></b> &apos;The Lord said to my Lord, &ldquo;Sit at my right hand until I put your enemies under your feet&rdquo; &apos;?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 110:1."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="22:45">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:45">45</span></font></b> If then David calls him &apos;Lord,&apos; how is he his son?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="22:46">46</span></font></b> And no one was able to answer him a word, nor did anyone dare from that day <i>[on]</i> to ask him any more <i>[questions]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The word &ldquo;<i>[questions]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:1">23:1</span></font></b> Then Jesus spoke to the crowds and to his disciples, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:2">2</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;The scribes and the Pharisees sit on the seat of Moses. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:3">3</span></font></b> Therefore do and observe everything that they tell you, but do not do as <u>they do</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;their deeds.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for they tell <i>[others to do something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[others to do something]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and do not do <i>[it themselves]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[it themselves]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:4">4</span></font></b> And they tie up heavy burdens<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;burdens that are heavy and hard to bear.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and put <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on people&apos;s shoulders, but <i>[they]</i> themselves are not willing with their finger to move them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:5">5</span></font></b> And they do all their deeds in order to be seen by people, for they make their phylacteries broad and make their<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tassels long. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:6">6</span></font></b> And they love the place of honor at banquets and the best seats in the synagogues <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:7">7</span></font></b> and the greetings in the marketplaces and to be called &apos;Rabbi&apos; by people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:8">8</span></font></b> But you are not to be called &apos;Rabbi,&apos; because one is your teacher, and you are all brothers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:9">9</span></font></b> And do not call <i>[anyone]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> your father on earth, for one is your heavenly Father. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:10">10</span></font></b> And do not be called teachers, because one is your teacher, the Christ. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:11">11</span></font></b> And the greatest among you will be your servant. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:12">12</span></font></b> And whoever exalts himself will be humbled, and whoever humbles himself will be exalted. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:13">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:13">13</span></font></b> &ldquo;But woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you shut the kingdom of heaven before people! For you do not enter, nor permit those wanting to go in<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the present tense has been translated as voluntative (&ldquo;wanting to go in&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to enter.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The most important Greek manuscripts omit v. 14, &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you devour widows&apos; houses and for show you pray long prayers! Therefore you will receive the greater condemnation.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:15">15</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you travel around the sea and the dry <i>[land]</i> to make one convert, and when he becomes <i>[one]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> you make him twice as much a son of hell <i>[as]</i> you <i>[are]</i>! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, blind guides, who say, &apos;Whoever swears by the temple, it is nothing! But whoever swears by the gold of the temple is bound <i>[by his oath]</i>.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The phrase &ldquo;<i>[by his oath]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:17">17</span></font></b> Fools and blind <i>[people]</i>! For which is greater, the gold or the temple that makes the gold holy? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:18">18</span></font></b> And, &apos;Whoever swears by the altar, it is nothing! But whoever swears by the gift <i>[that is]</i> on it is bound <i>[by his oath]</i>.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The phrase &ldquo;<i>[by his oath]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:19">19</span></font></b> Blind <i>[people]</i>! For which <i>[is]</i> greater, the gift or the altar that makes the gift holy? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:20">20</span></font></b> Therefore the one who swears by the altar swears by it and by everything <i>[that is]</i> on it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:21">21</span></font></b> And the one who swears by the temple swears by it and by the one who dwells <i>[in]</i> it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:22">22</span></font></b> And the one who swears by heaven swears by the throne of God and by the one who sits on it. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:23">23</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you pay a tenth of mint and dill and cumin, and neglect the more important <i>[matters]</i> of the law--justice and mercy and faithfulness! It was necessary<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;But it was necessary.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to do these <i>[things]</i> <u>while not neglecting those</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;and those not to neglect.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:24">24</span></font></b> Blind guides who filter out a gnat and swallow a camel! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:25">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:25">25</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you cleanse the outside of the cup and the dish, but inside they are full of greed and self-indulgence! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:26">26</span></font></b> Blind Pharisee! First clean the inside of the cup and the dish,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;and the dish.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> so that the outside of it may become clean also. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:27">27</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you are like whitewashed tombs which on the outside appear beautiful, but on the inside are full of the bones of the dead and of everything unclean! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:28">28</span></font></b> In the <i>[same]</i> way, on the outside you also appear righteous to people, but inside you are full of hypocrisy and lawlessness. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:29">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:29">29</span></font></b> &ldquo;Woe to you, scribes and Pharisees--hypocrites!--because you build the tombs of the prophets and decorate the graves of the righteous, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:30">30</span></font></b> and you say, &apos;If we had lived in the days of our fathers, we would not have been partners with them in the blood of the prophets!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:31">31</span></font></b> Thus you testify against yourselves that you are descendants of those who murdered the prophets! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:32">32</span></font></b> And you--fill up the measure of your fathers! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:33">33</span></font></b> Serpents! Offspring of vipers! How will you escape from the condemnation to hell? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:34">34</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i>, behold, I am sending to you prophets and wise men and scribes. <i>[Some]</i> of them you will kill and crucify, and some of them you will flog in your synagogues and will pursue from town to town, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:35">35</span></font></b> so that upon you will come all the righteous blood shed on the earth from the blood of righteous Abel up to the blood of Zechariah son of Barachiah, whom you murdered between the temple and the altar. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:36">36</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, all these <i>[things]</i> will come upon this generation! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="23:37">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:37">37</span></font></b> &ldquo;Jerusalem, Jerusalem, who kills the prophets and stones those who are sent to her! How many times I wanted to gather your children together <u>the way</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the manner in which.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a hen gathers her young together under <i>[her]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wings, and you were not willing! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:38">38</span></font></b> Behold, your house has been left to you desolate! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="23:39">39</span></font></b> For I tell you, you will never see me from now <i>[on]</i> until you say, &apos;Blessed <i>[is]</i> the one who comes in the name of the Lord!&apos;&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 118:26."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:1">24:1</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i> Jesus went out of the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was going along, and his disciples came up to point out to him the buildings of the temple. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:2">2</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Do you not see all these <i>[things]</i>? Truly I say to you, not <i>[one]</i> stone will be left here on <i>[another]</i> stone that will not be thrown down!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:3">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:3">3</span></font></b> And <i>[as]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was sitting&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was sitting on the Mount of Olives, the disciples came up to him privately, saying, &ldquo;Tell us, when will these <i>[things]</i> happen, and what <i>[will be]</i> the sign of your coming and of the end of the age?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:4">4</span></font></b> And Jesus answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Watch out that no one deceives you! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:5">5</span></font></b> For many will come in my name, saying, &apos;I am the Christ,&apos; and they will deceive many. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:6">6</span></font></b> And you are going to hear about wars and rumors of wars. See to it that you are not alarmed, for this must happen, but the end is not yet. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:7">7</span></font></b> For nation will rise up against nation and kingdom against kingdom, and there will be famines and earthquakes in <i>[various]</i> places.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;in place after place.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:8">8</span></font></b> But all these <i>[things]</i> <i>[are]</i> the beginning of birth pains. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:9">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:9">9</span></font></b> &ldquo;Then they will hand you over to persecution and will kill you, and you will be hated by all the nations<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> because of my name. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:10">10</span></font></b> And then many will be led into sin and will betray one another and will hate one another, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:11">11</span></font></b> and many false prophets will appear and will deceive many, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:12">12</span></font></b> and because lawlessness will increase, the love of many will grow cold. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:13">13</span></font></b> But the one who endures to the end--this person will be saved. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:14">14</span></font></b> And this gospel of the kingdom will be proclaimed in the whole inhabited earth for a testimony to all the nations,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo;; the same Greek word can be translated &ldquo;nations&rdquo; or &ldquo;Gentiles&rdquo; depending on the context."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and then the end will come. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:15">15</span></font></b> &ldquo;So when you see the abomination of desolation<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An allusion to Dan 9:27."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spoken about by the prophet Daniel standing in the holy place&rdquo; (let the one who reads understand), <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:16">16</span></font></b> &ldquo;then those in Judea must flee to the mountains! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:17">17</span></font></b> The one who is on his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> housetop must not come down to take things out of his house, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:18">18</span></font></b> and the one who is in the field must not turn back to pick up his cloak. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:19">19</span></font></b> And woe to those <u>who are pregnant</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;who have in the womb.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and to those who are nursing <i>[their babies]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[their babies]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are supplied as a necessary clarification."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in those days! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:20">20</span></font></b> But pray that your flight may not happen in winter or on a Sabbath. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:21">21</span></font></b> For at that time there will be great tribulation, such as has not happened from the beginning of the world until now, nor ever will happen. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:22">22</span></font></b> And unless those days had been shortened, <u>no human being would be saved</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;every flesh would not be saved.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> But for the sake of the elect, those days will be shortened. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:23">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:23">23</span></font></b> &ldquo;At that time if anyone should say to you, &apos;Behold, here <i>[is]</i> the Christ,&apos; or &apos;Here <i>[he is]</i>,&apos; do not believe <i>[him]</i>!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:24">24</span></font></b> For false messiahs and false prophets will appear, and will produce great signs and wonders in order to deceive, if possible, even the elect. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:25">25</span></font></b> Behold, I have told you ahead of time! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:26">26</span></font></b> Therefore if they say to you, &apos;Behold, he is in the wilderness,&apos; do not go out, <i>[or]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[or]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because of English style."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;Behold, he is in the inner rooms,&apos; do not believe <i>[it]</i>!<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:27">27</span></font></b> For just as the lightning comes from the east and flashes to the west, so the coming of the Son of Man will be. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:28">28</span></font></b> Wherever the corpse is, there the vultures will gather. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:29">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:29">29</span></font></b> &ldquo;And immediately after the tribulation of those days, &apos;the sun will be darkened and the moon will not give its light, and the stars will fall from heaven, and the powers of heaven will be shaken.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Isa 13:10; 34:4."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:30">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:30">30</span></font></b> And then the sign of the Son of Man will appear in heaven,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;the sky.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and then all the tribes of the earth will mourn, and they will see the Son of Man arriving on the clouds of heaven<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;the sky.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with power and great glory. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:31">31</span></font></b> And he will send out his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will gather his elect together from the four winds, from <i>[one]</i> end of heaven<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;of the sky.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the <i>[other]</i> end of it. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:32">32</span></font></b> &ldquo;Now learn the parable from the fig tree: Whenever its branch has already become tender and puts forth its<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> leaves, you know that summer <i>[is]</i> near. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:33">33</span></font></b> So also you, when you see all these <i>[things]</i>, know<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;you know.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that he is near, at the door. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:34">34</span></font></b> Truly I say to you that this generation will never pass away until all these <i>[things]</i> take place! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:35">35</span></font></b> Heaven and earth will pass away, but my words will never pass away. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:36">36</span></font></b> &ldquo;But concerning that day and hour no one knows--not even the angels of heaven nor the Son--except the Father alone. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:37">37</span></font></b> For just as the days of Noah <i>[were]</i>, so the coming of the Son of Man will be. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:38">38</span></font></b> For as in the days<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts have &ldquo;those days.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> before the flood they were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, until the day Noah entered into the ark. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:39">39</span></font></b> And they did not know <i>[anything]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> until the deluge came and swept <i>[them]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> all away. So also the coming of the Son of Man will be. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:40">40</span></font></b> Then there will be two men in the field; one will be taken and one left. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:41">41</span></font></b> Two women will be grinding at the mill; one will be taken and one left. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:42">42</span></font></b> Therefore be on the alert, because you do not know what day your Lord is coming! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:43">43</span></font></b> But understand this: that if the master of the house had known what watch of the night the thief was coming, he would have stayed awake and would not have let his house be broken into. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:44">44</span></font></b> For this <i>[reason]</i> you also must be ready, because the Son of Man is coming at an hour that you do not think <i>[he will come]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[he will come]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="24:45">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:45">45</span></font></b> &ldquo;Who then is the faithful and wise slave whom the master has put in charge of his household slaves to give them their<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> food at the right time? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:46">46</span></font></b> Blessed <i>[is]</i> that slave whom his master will find so doing <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;comes back&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> comes back. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:47">47</span></font></b> Truly I say to you that he will put him in charge of all his possessions. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:48">48</span></font></b> But if that evil slave should say <u>to himself</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in his heart.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &apos;My master is staying away for a long time,&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:49">49</span></font></b> and he begins to beat his fellow slaves and eats and drinks with drunkards, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:50">50</span></font></b> the master of that slave will come on a day that he does not expect and at an hour that he does not know, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="24:51">51</span></font></b> and will cut him in two and assign his place with the hypocrites. In that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:1">25:1</span></font></b> &ldquo;Then the kingdom of heaven may be compared to ten virgins who took their lamps <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went out to meet the bridegroom. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:2">2</span></font></b> Now five of them were foolish and five <i>[were]</i> wise. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:3">3</span></font></b> For <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the foolish ones took their lamps, they did not take olive oil with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:4">4</span></font></b> But the wise ones took olive oil in flasks with their lamps. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:5">5</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was delayed&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the bridegroom was delayed, they all became drowsy and fell asleep.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to sleep&rdquo;, &ldquo;fell asleep&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:6">6</span></font></b> But in the middle of the night there was a shout, &apos;Behold, the bridegroom! Come out to meet him!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:7">7</span></font></b> Then all those virgins woke up and trimmed their lamps. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:8">8</span></font></b> And the foolish ones said to the wise ones, &apos;Give us <i>[some]</i> of your olive oil, because our lamps are going out!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:9">9</span></font></b> But the wise ones answered saying, &ldquo;Certainly there will never be enough for us and for you! Go instead to those who sell <i>[olive oil]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and buy <i>[some]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for yourselves.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:10">10</span></font></b> But <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had gone away&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had gone away to buy <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the bridegroom arrived, and those who were ready went inside with him to the wedding celebration, and the door was shut. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:11">11</span></font></b> And later the other virgins came also, saying, &apos;Lord, lord, open <i>[the door]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for us!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:12">12</span></font></b> But he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;Truly I say to you, I do not know you!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:13">13</span></font></b> Therefore be on the alert, because you do not know the day or the hour! </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:14">14</span></font></b> For <i>[it is]</i> like a man going on a journey. He summoned his own slaves and handed over his property to them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:15">15</span></font></b> And to one he gave five talents, and to another two, and to another one, to each one according to his own ability, and he went on a journey immediately. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:16">16</span></font></b> The one who had received the five talents went out <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> traded with them and gained five more. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:17">17</span></font></b> In the same way the one <i>[who had]</i> the two gained two more. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:18">18</span></font></b> But the one who had received the one went away <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> dug up the ground and hid his master&apos;s money. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:19">19</span></font></b> Now after a long time, the master of those slaves came and settled accounts with them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:20">20</span></font></b> And the one who had received the five talents came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> brought five more talents, saying, &apos;Master, you handed over to me five talents. See, I have gained five more talents!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:21">21</span></font></b> His master said to him, &apos;Well done, good and faithful slave! You were faithful over a few <i>[things]</i>; I will put you <i>[in charge]</i> over many <i>[things]</i>. Enter into the joy of your master!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:22">22</span></font></b> And the one <i>[who had]</i> the two talents also came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;Master, you handed over to me two talents. See, I have gained two talents more!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:23">23</span></font></b> His master said to him, &apos;Well done, good and faithful slave! You were faithful over a few <i>[things]</i>; I will put you <i>[in charge]</i> over many <i>[things]</i>. Enter into the joy of your master!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:24">24</span></font></b> And the one who had received the one talent came up also <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &apos;Master, <i>[because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;knew&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> knew you, that you are a hard man, reaping where you did not sow and gathering from where you did not scatter <i>[seed]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:25">25</span></font></b> And <i>[because I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[because]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;was afraid&rdquo;) which is understood as causal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was afraid, I went away <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hid your talent in the ground. See, you have <i>[what is]</i> yours!&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:26">26</span></font></b> But his master answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &apos;Evil and lazy slave! You knew that I reap where I did not sow and gather from where I did not scatter <i>[seed]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:27">27</span></font></b> Then you ought to have deposited my money with the bankers, and <i>[when I]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;returned&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> returned I would have gotten back <i>[what was]</i> mine with interest! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:28">28</span></font></b> Therefore take the talent from him and give <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the one who has the ten talents. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:29">29</span></font></b> For to everyone who has, <i>[more]</i> will be given, and he will have an abundance. But from the one who does not have, even what he has will be taken away from him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:30">30</span></font></b> And throw the worthless slave into the outer darkness--in that place there will be weeping and gnashing of teeth!&apos; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="25:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:31">31</span></font></b> Now when the Son of Man comes in his glory and all the angels with him, then he will sit on his glorious throne. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:32">32</span></font></b> And all the nations will be gathered before him, and he will separate them from one another like a shepherd separates the sheep from the goats. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:33">33</span></font></b> And he will place the sheep on his right and the goats on the left. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:34">34</span></font></b> Then the king will say to those on his right, &apos;Come, <i>[you]</i> who are blessed by my Father. Inherit the kingdom prepared for you from the foundation of the world! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:35">35</span></font></b> For I was hungry and you gave me <i>[something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to eat, I was thirsty and you gave me <i>[something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to drink, I was a stranger and you welcomed me as a guest, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:36">36</span></font></b> I was naked and you clothed me, I was sick and you cared for me, I was in prison and you came to me.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:37">37</span></font></b> Then the righteous will answer him, saying, &apos;Lord, when did we see you hungry and feed <i>[you]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> or thirsty and give <i>[you something]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to drink? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:38">38</span></font></b> And when did we see you a stranger and welcome <i>[you]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as a guest, or naked and clothe <i>[you]</i>?<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:39">39</span></font></b> And when did we see you sick or in prison and come to you?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:40">40</span></font></b> And the king will answer <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;will answer&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> say to them, &apos;Truly I say to you, in as much as you did <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to one of the least of these brothers of mine, you did <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to me.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:41">41</span></font></b> Then he will also say to those on <i>[his]</i> left, &apos;Depart from me, <i>[you]</i> accursed ones, into the eternal fire that has been prepared for the devil and his angels! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:42">42</span></font></b> For I was hungry and you did not give me <i>[anything]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to eat, I was thirsty and you did not give me <i>[anything]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to drink, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:43">43</span></font></b> I was a stranger and you did not welcome me as a guest, naked and you did not clothe me, sick and in prison and you did not care for me.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:44">44</span></font></b> Then they will also answer, saying, &apos;Lord, when did we see you hungry or thirsty or a stranger or naked or sick or in prison and not serve you?&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:45">45</span></font></b> Then he will answer them, saying, &apos;Truly I say to you, in as much as you did not do <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to one of the least of these, you did not do <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to me.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="25:46">46</span></font></b> And these will depart into eternal punishment, but the righteous into eternal life.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:1">26:1</span></font></b> And it happened that when Jesus had finished all these sayings, he said to his disciples, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:2">2</span></font></b> &ldquo;You know that after two days the Passover takes place, and the Son of Man will be handed over<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;will be delivered up.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in order to be crucified.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:3">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:3">3</span></font></b> Then the chief priests and the elders of the people assembled in the palace of the high priest, who was named Caiaphas, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:4">4</span></font></b> and plotted in order that they could arrest Jesus by stealth and kill <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:5">5</span></font></b> But they were saying, &ldquo;Not during the feast, so that there will not be an uproar among the people.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:6">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:6">6</span></font></b> Now <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Jesus was at Bethany in the house of Simon the leper, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:7">7</span></font></b> a woman came up to him holding an alabaster flask of very expensive perfumed oil, and poured <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> out on his head <i>[while he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was reclining at table&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was reclining at table. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:8">8</span></font></b> And <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> the disciples saw <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were indignant, saying, &ldquo;<u>Why</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for what&rdquo; <i>[reason]</i>."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this waste? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:9">9</span></font></b> For this could have been sold for a large sum and given to the poor!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:10">10</span></font></b> But Jesus, knowing <i>[this]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Why do you cause trouble for the woman? For she has done a good deed for me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:11">11</span></font></b> For the poor you always have with you, but you do not always have me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:12">12</span></font></b> For <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;poured&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> this woman poured this ointment on my body, she did <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in order to prepare me for burial. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:13">13</span></font></b> Truly I say to you, wherever this gospel is proclaimed in the whole world, what this woman has done will also be told in memory of her.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:14">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:14">14</span></font></b> Then one of the twelve, the one named Judas Iscariot, went to the chief priests <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:15">15</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle in the previous verse (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;What are you willing to give me if I in turn deliver him to you?&rdquo; So they set out for him thirty silver coins. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:16">16</span></font></b> And from that time on, he began seeking a favorable opportunity in order that he could betray him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:17">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:17">17</span></font></b> Now on the first <i>[day]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the word &ldquo;<i>[day]</i>&rdquo; is not in the Greek text but is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> of the feast of Unleavened Bread the disciples came up to Jesus, saying, &ldquo;Where do you want us to prepare for you to eat the Passover?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:18">18</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;Go into the city to a certain man and tell him, &apos;The Teacher says, &ldquo;My time is near. I am celebrating the Passover with you with my disciples.&rdquo; &apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:19">19</span></font></b> And the disciples did as Jesus directed them, and they prepared the Passover. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:20">20</span></font></b> And <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was evening, he was reclining at table with the twelve disciples.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Some manuscripts omit &ldquo;disciples.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:21">21</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were eating&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were eating he said, &ldquo;Truly I say to you, that one of you will betray me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:22">22</span></font></b> And greatly distressed, each one began to say to him, &ldquo;<u>Surely I am not he, am I</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;surely I am not&rdquo;; the negative construction in Greek anticipates a negative answer here, indicated in the translation by &ldquo;am I.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Lord?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:23">23</span></font></b> And he answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;The one who dips his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand in the bowl with me--this one will betray me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:24">24</span></font></b> The Son of Man is going just as it is written about him, but woe to that man by whom the Son of Man is betrayed! It would be better for him if that man had not been born.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:25">25</span></font></b> And Judas, the one who was betraying him, answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;<u>Surely I am not he, am I</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;surely I am not&rdquo;; the negative construction in Greek anticipates a negative answer here, indicated in the translation by &ldquo;am I.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Rabbi?&rdquo; He said to him, &ldquo;You have said <i>[it]</i>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:26">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:26">26</span></font></b> Now <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were eating&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were eating Jesus took bread and, <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;giving thanks&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> giving thanks, he broke <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and giving <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to the disciples, he said, &ldquo;Take, eat, this is my body.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:27">27</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;taking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> taking the cup and giving thanks he gave <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to them, saying, &ldquo;Drink from it, all of you, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:28">28</span></font></b> for this is my blood of the covenant which is poured out for many for the forgiveness of sins. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:29">29</span></font></b> But I tell you, from now <i>[on]</i> I will never drink of this fruit of the vine until that day when I drink it new with you in the kingdom of my Father.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:30">30</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had sung the hymn&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had sung the hymn, they went out to the Mount of Olives. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:31">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:31">31</span></font></b> Then Jesus said to them, &ldquo;You will all fall away because of me during this night, for it is written, &apos;I will strike the shepherd and the sheep of the flock will be scattered.&apos;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Zech 13:7."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:32">32</span></font></b> But after I am raised, I will go ahead of you into Galilee.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:33">33</span></font></b> But Peter answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;If they all fall away because of you, I will never fall away!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:34">34</span></font></b> Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Truly I say to you that during this night, before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:35">35</span></font></b> Peter said to him, &ldquo;Even if it is necessary for me to die with you, I will never deny you!&rdquo; And all the disciples said the same <i>[thing]</i>. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:36">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:36">36</span></font></b> Then Jesus went with them to a place called Gethsemane, and he said to the disciples, &ldquo;Sit here while I go over there <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> pray.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:37">37</span></font></b> And taking along Peter and the two sons of Zebedee, he began to be distressed and troubled. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:38">38</span></font></b> Then he said to them, &ldquo;My soul is deeply grieved, to the point of death. Remain here and stay awake with me.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:39">39</span></font></b> And going forward a little he fell down on his face, praying and saying, &ldquo;My Father, if it is possible, let this cup pass from me. Nevertheless, not as I will, but as you <i>[will]</i>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the verb &ldquo;<i>[will]</i>&rdquo; is an understood repetition of the verb earlier in this verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:40">40</span></font></b> And he came to the disciples and found them sleeping, and he said to Peter, &ldquo;So, were you not able to stay awake with me one hour? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:41">41</span></font></b> Stay awake and pray that you will not enter into temptation. The spirit <i>[is]</i> willing, but the flesh <i>[is]</i> weak!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:42">42</span></font></b> Again for the second time he went away <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prayed, saying, &ldquo;My Father, if this cannot pass unless I drink it, your will must be done.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:43">43</span></font></b> And he came again <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came again&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> found them sleeping, <u>for they could not keep their eyes open</u>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for their eyes were weighed down.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:44">44</span></font></b> And leaving them again, he went away <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> prayed for the third <i>[time]</i>, saying the same thing again. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:45">45</span></font></b> Then he came to the disciples and said to them, &ldquo;Are you still sleeping and resting? Behold, the hour is near, and the Son of Man is being betrayed into the hands of sinners. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:46">46</span></font></b> Get up, let us go! Behold, the one who is betraying me is approaching!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:47">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:47">47</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was ... speaking&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was still speaking, behold, Judas--one of the twelve--arrived, and with him a large crowd with swords and clubs, from the chief priests and elders of the people. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:48">48</span></font></b> Now the one who was betraying him had given them a sign, saying, &ldquo;<i>[The one]</i> whom I kiss--he is <i>[the one]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the predicate nominative (&ldquo;<i>[the one]</i>&rdquo;) is implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Arrest him!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:49">49</span></font></b> And he came up to Jesus immediately <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;Greetings, Rabbi,&rdquo; and kissed him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:50">50</span></font></b> And Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Friend, <i>[do that]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[do that]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for which you have come.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The meaning of this phrase is disputed: (1) some take it as a declarative (as in the translation); (2) others understand it as some form of a question, often with supplied words: (a) &ldquo;Friend, <i>[are you misusing the kiss]</i> for that <i>[purpose]</i> for which you are here?&rdquo; (b) &ldquo;Friend, in connection with that for which you have appeared <i>[do you kiss me]</i>?&rdquo; (c) &ldquo;Friend, are you here for this purpose?&rdquo; (d) &ldquo;Friend, what are you here for?&rdquo;; this last option, though often suggested, is doubtful because of lack of evidence for the relative pronoun used as an interrogative in direct questions."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Then they came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> laid hands on Jesus and arrested him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:51">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:51">51</span></font></b> And behold, one of those with Jesus extended his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hand <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;extended&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> drew his sword, and striking the slave of the high priest, cut off his ear. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:52">52</span></font></b> Then Jesus said to him, &ldquo;Put your sword back into its place! For all who take up the sword will die by the sword. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:53">53</span></font></b> Or do you think that I cannot call upon my Father, and he would put at my disposal at once more than twelve legions of angels? <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:54">54</span></font></b> How then would the scriptures be fulfilled that it must happen in this way?&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:55">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:55">55</span></font></b> At that time Jesus said to the crowds, &ldquo;Have you come out with swords and clubs, as against a robber, to arrest me? Every day in the temple <i>[courts]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[courts]</i>&rdquo; is supplied to distinguish this area from the interior of the temple building itself."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> I sat teaching, and you did not arrest me! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:56">56</span></font></b> But all this has happened in order that the scriptures of the prophets would be fulfilled.&rdquo; Then the disciples all abandoned him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;abandoned&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> fled. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:57">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:57">57</span></font></b> Now those who had arrested Jesus led <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> away to Caiaphas the high priest, where the scribes and the elders had gathered. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:58">58</span></font></b> But Peter was following him from a distance, as far as the courtyard of the high priest. And he went inside <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was sitting with the officers to see the outcome. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:59">59</span></font></b> Now the chief priests and the whole Sanhedrin were looking for false testimony against Jesus in order that they could put him to death. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:60">60</span></font></b> And they did not find <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[although]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[although]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came forward&rdquo;) which is understood as concessive."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> many false witnesses came forward. And finally two came forward <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:61">61</span></font></b> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the participle in the previous verse (&ldquo;came forward&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;This man said, &apos;I am able to destroy the temple of God and rebuild <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> within three days.&apos;&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:62">62</span></font></b> And the high priest stood up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stood up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to him, &ldquo;Do you reply nothing? What are these <i>[people]</i> testifying against you?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:63">63</span></font></b> But Jesus was silent. And the high priest said to him, &ldquo;I put you under oath by the living God, that you tell us if you are the Christ, the Son of God!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:64">64</span></font></b> Jesus said to him, &ldquo;You have said <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> But I tell you, from now <i>[on]</i> you will see the Son of Man sitting at the right hand of the Power<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="An indirect way of referring to God."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> and coming on the clouds of heaven.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:65">65</span></font></b> Then the high priest tore his robes, saying, &ldquo;He has blasphemed! What further need do we have of witnesses? Behold, you have just now heard the blasphemy! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:66">66</span></font></b> What do you think?&rdquo; And they answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;<u>He deserves death</u>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;he is deserving of death.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:67">67</span></font></b> Then they spat in his face and struck him with their fists, and they slapped <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:68">68</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Prophesy for us, <i>[you]</i> Christ! Who is it who hit you?&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="26:69">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:69">69</span></font></b> Now Peter was sitting outside in the courtyard, and a female slave came up to him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;You also were with Jesus the Galilean.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:70">70</span></font></b> But he denied <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in the presence of <i>[them]</i> all, saying, &ldquo;I do not know what you mean!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:71">71</span></font></b> And <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;went out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went out to the gateway, another <i>[female slave]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[female slave]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied by the feminine singular form."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw him and said to those <i>[who were]</i> there, &ldquo;This man was with Jesus the Nazarene.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:72">72</span></font></b> And again he denied <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with an oath, &ldquo;I do not know the man!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:73">73</span></font></b> And after a little <i>[while]</i> those who were standing there came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to Peter, &ldquo;You really are <i>[one]</i> of them also, because even your accent <u>reveals who you are</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;makes you evident.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:74">74</span></font></b> Then he began to curse and to swear with an oath, &ldquo;I do not know the man!&rdquo; And immediately a rooster crowed. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="26:75">75</span></font></b> And Peter remembered the statement Jesus had said, &ldquo;Before the rooster crows, you will deny me three times,&rdquo; and he went outside <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wept bitterly. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:1">27:1</span></font></b> Now <i>[when it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> was early morning, all the chief priests and the elders of the people took counsel against Jesus in order to put him to death. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:2">2</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;tying&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tying him up, they led <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> away and handed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> over to Pilate the governor. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:3">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:3">3</span></font></b> Then <i>[when]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Judas, the one who had betrayed him, saw that he had been condemned, he regretted <i>[what he had done]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;regretted&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> returned the thirty silver coins to the chief priests and elders, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:4">4</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;I have sinned <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;betraying&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> betraying innocent blood!&rdquo; But they said, &ldquo;What <i>[is that]</i> to us? You see to <i>[it]</i>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:5">5</span></font></b> And throwing the silver coins into the temple he departed. And he went away <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went away&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hanged himself. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:6">6</span></font></b> But the chief priests took the silver coins <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;It is not permitted to put them into the temple treasury, because it is <u>blood money</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the price of blood.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:7">7</span></font></b> And <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;taking&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> taking counsel, they purchased <u>with</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;for.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> them the Potter&apos;s Field, for a burial place for strangers. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:8">8</span></font></b> (For this reason that field has been called the Field of Blood until today.) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:9">9</span></font></b> Then what was spoken by the prophet Jeremiah was fulfilled, who said, &ldquo;And they took the thirty silver coins, the price of the one who had been priced, <i>[on]</i> whom a price had been set by the sons of Israel, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:10">10</span></font></b> and they gave them for the potter&apos;s field, just as the Lord directed me.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from various passages in Jeremiah including 18:2-6; 19:1-13; 32:6-15; see also Zech 11:12-13."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:11">11</span></font></b> So Jesus stood before the governor, and the governor asked him, saying, &ldquo;Are you the king of the Jews?&rdquo; And Jesus said, &ldquo;You say <i>[so]</i>.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:12">12</span></font></b> And <u>when he was being accused</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;in the him being accused.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> by the chief priests and elders he answered nothing. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:13">13</span></font></b> Then Pilate said to him, &ldquo;Do you not hear how many <i>[things]</i> they are testifying against you?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:14">14</span></font></b> And he did not reply to him, not even with reference to one statement, so that the governor was very astonished. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:15">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:15">15</span></font></b> Now at each feast, the governor was accustomed to release one prisoner to the crowd--the one whom they wanted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:16">16</span></font></b> And at that time they had a notorious prisoner named Jesus<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Although many manuscripts omit &ldquo;Jesus&rdquo; here, it is so hard to explain why a scribe would have added it that the reading is probably original."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Barabbas.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="&ldquo;Barabbas&rdquo; means &ldquo;son of the father&rdquo; in Aramaic."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:17">17</span></font></b> So <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;had assembled&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they had assembled, Pilate said to them, &ldquo;Whom do you want me to release for you--Jesus<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Although many manuscripts omit &ldquo;Jesus&rdquo; here, it is so hard to explain why a scribe would have added it that the reading is probably original."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Barabbas or Jesus who is called Christ?&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:18">18</span></font></b> (For he knew that they had handed him over because of envy. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:19">19</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;was sitting&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he was sitting on the judgment seat, his wife sent <i>[a message]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to him, saying, &ldquo;<u>Have nothing to do with that righteous man</u>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;nothing to you and to that righteous man.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> for I have suffered much as a result of a dream today because of him.&rdquo;) <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:20">20</span></font></b> But the chief priests and the elders persuaded the crowds that they should ask for Barabbas and put Jesus to death. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:21">21</span></font></b> So the governor answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to them, &ldquo;Which of the two do you want me to release for you?&rdquo; And they said, &ldquo;Barabbas!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:22">22</span></font></b> Pilate said to them, &ldquo;What then should I do <i>[with]</i> Jesus, the one who is called Christ?&rdquo; They all said, &ldquo;Let him be crucified!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:23">23</span></font></b> And he said, &ldquo;Why? What wrong has he done?&rdquo; But they began to shout<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as ingressive here (&ldquo;began to shout&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> even louder, saying, &ldquo;Let him be crucified!&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:24">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:24">24</span></font></b> So Pilate, <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw that he was accomplishing nothing, but instead an uproar was developing, took water <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> washed his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> hands before the crowd, saying, &ldquo;I am innocent of the blood of this man. You see to <i>[it]</i>!&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:25">25</span></font></b> And all the people answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;His blood <i>[be]</i> on us and on our children!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:26">26</span></font></b> Then he released Barabbas for them, but <i>[after]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;flogged&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he had Jesus flogged, he handed <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> over so that he could be crucified. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:27">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:27">27</span></font></b> Then the soldiers of the governor took Jesus into the governor&apos;s residence <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gathered the whole cohort to him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:28">28</span></font></b> And they stripped him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;stripped&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> put a scarlet military cloak around him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:29">29</span></font></b> and weaving a crown of thorns, they put <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on his head, and <i>[put]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="This is an understood repetition of the verb from earlier in the verse."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> a reed in his right hand. And kneeling down before him, they mocked him, saying, &ldquo;Hail, king of the Jews!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:30">30</span></font></b> And they spat on him <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;spat&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took the reed and repeatedly struck<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The imperfect tense has been translated as iterative here (&ldquo;repeatedly struck&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on his head. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:31">31</span></font></b> And when they had mocked him, they stripped him of the military cloak and put his <i>[own]</i> clothes on him, and led him away in order to crucify <i>[him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:32">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:32">32</span></font></b> And <i>[as they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[as]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;were going out&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were going out, they found a man of Cyrene <u>named</u><font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;by name.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> Simon. They forced this man to carry his cross. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:33">33</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> came to a place called Golgotha (which <u>means Place of a Skull</u>),<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;is called Place of a Skull.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:34">34</span></font></b> they gave him wine mixed with gall to drink, and <i>[when he]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;tasted&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> tasted <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> he did not want to drink <i>[it]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:35">35</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had crucified&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had crucified him, they divided his clothes among themselves<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;among themselves&rdquo; reflects the middle voice of the verb &ldquo;divided.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;casting&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> casting lots. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:36">36</span></font></b> And they sat down <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;sat down&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> were watching over him there. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:37">37</span></font></b> And they put above his head the charge against him <u>in writing</u>:<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;written.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;This is Jesus, the king of the Jews.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:38">38</span></font></b> Then two robbers were crucified with him, one on <i>[his]</i> right and one on <i>[his]</i> left. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:39">39</span></font></b> And those who passed by reviled him, shaking their heads <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:40">40</span></font></b> and saying, &ldquo;The one who would destroy the temple and rebuild <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> in three days, save yourself! If you are the Son of God, come down from the cross!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:41">41</span></font></b> In the same way also the chief priests, along with the scribes and elders, were mocking <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saying, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:42">42</span></font></b> &ldquo;He saved others; he is not able to save himself! He is the king of Israel! Let him come down now from the cross, and we will believe in him! <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:43">43</span></font></b> He trusts in God; let him deliver him now if he wants to,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;let him deliver <i>[him]</i> now if he wants him.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> because he said, &apos;I am the Son of God&apos;!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:44">44</span></font></b> And in the same <i>[way]</i> even the robbers who were crucified with him were reviling him. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:45">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:45">45</span></font></b> Now from the sixth hour, darkness came over all the land until the ninth hour. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:46">46</span></font></b> And about the ninth hour Jesus cried out with a loud voice, saying, &ldquo;Eli, Eli, lema sabachthani?&rdquo; (that is, &ldquo;My God, my God, why have you forsaken me?&rdquo;)<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="A quotation from Ps 22:1."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:47">47</span></font></b> And some of those who were standing there, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;heard&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> heard <i>[it]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said, &ldquo;This man is summoning Elijah!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:48">48</span></font></b> And immediately one of them ran and took a sponge and filled <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> with sour wine and put <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on a reed <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participles (&ldquo;ran ... took ... filled ... put&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to him to drink. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:49">49</span></font></b> But the others said, &ldquo;Leave <i>[him]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> alone! let us see if Elijah is coming to save him.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:50">50</span></font></b> And Jesus cried out again with a loud voice <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;cried out&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> gave up his<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;the&rdquo;; the Greek article is used here as a possessive pronoun."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spirit. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:51">51</span></font></b> And behold, the curtain of the temple was torn in two from top to bottom, and the earth shook and the rocks were split. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:52">52</span></font></b> And the tombs were opened, and many bodies of the saints who had fallen asleep were raised, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:53">53</span></font></b> and coming out of the tombs after his resurrection, they went into the holy city and appeared to many. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:54">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:54">54</span></font></b> Now the centurion and those with him who were guarding Jesus, <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw the earthquake and the things that took place, were extremely frightened, saying, &ldquo;Truly this man was God&apos;s Son!&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:55">55</span></font></b> And there were many women there, observing from a distance, who had followed Jesus from Galilee, serving him, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:56">56</span></font></b> among whom were Mary Magdalene, and Mary the mother of James and Joseph, and the mother of the sons of Zebedee. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:57">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:57">57</span></font></b> Now <i>[when it]</i> was evening, a rich man from Arimathea named Joseph came, who also was a disciple of Jesus himself. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:58">58</span></font></b> This man approached Pilate <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> asked for the body of Jesus. Then Pilate ordered <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> to be given <i>[to him]</i>.<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="The words &ldquo;<i>[to him]</i>&rdquo; are not in the Greek text but are implied."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:59">59</span></font></b> And Joseph took the body <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> wrapped it in a clean linen cloth, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:60">60</span></font></b> and placed it in his <i>[own]</i> new tomb that he had cut in the rock. And he rolled a large stone to the entrance of the tomb <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;rolled&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> went away. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:61">61</span></font></b> Now Mary Magdalene and the other Mary were there, sitting opposite the tomb. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="27:62">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:62">62</span></font></b> Now <i>[on]</i> the next day, which is after the day of preparation, the chief priests and the Pharisees assembled before Pilate, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:63">63</span></font></b> saying, &ldquo;Sir, we remember that <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;alive&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> that deceiver was still alive he said, &apos;After three days I will rise.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:64">64</span></font></b> Therefore give orders that the tomb be made secure until the third day, lest his disciples come <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;come&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> steal him and tell the people, &apos;He has been raised from the dead,&apos; and the last deception will be worse than the first.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:65">65</span></font></b> Pilate said to them, &ldquo;You have a guard of soldiers. Go, make <i>[it]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> as secure as you know how.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="27:66">66</span></font></b> So they went with the guard of soldiers <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> made the tomb secure <i>[by]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[by]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;sealing&rdquo;) which is understood as means."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> sealing the stone. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:1">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:1">28:1</span></font></b> Now after the Sabbath, at the dawning on the first <i>[day]</i> of the week, Mary Magdalene and the other Mary came to view the tomb. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:2">2</span></font></b> And behold, there was a great earthquake, for an angel of the Lord descended from heaven and came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participles (&ldquo;descended&rdquo; and &ldquo;came up&rdquo;) have been translated as finite verbs."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> rolled away the stone and sat down<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Or &ldquo;was sitting&rdquo;; here &ldquo;sat down&rdquo; reflects an ingressive nuance (beginning of a process or entry into a state) in the translation of the imperfect verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> on it. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:3">3</span></font></b> Now his appearance was like lightning and his clothing white as snow. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:4">4</span></font></b> And the guards trembled from the fear of him and became like dead men. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:5">5</span></font></b> But the angel answered <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;answered&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> said to the women, &ldquo;Do not be afraid, for I know that you are looking for Jesus, who was crucified. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:6">6</span></font></b> He is not here, for he has been raised, just as he said. Come, see the place where he was lying. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:7">7</span></font></b> And go quickly, tell his disciples, &apos;He has been raised from the dead, and behold, he is going ahead of you into Galilee. You will see him there.&apos; Behold, I have told you.&rdquo; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:8">8</span></font></b> And they departed quickly from the tomb with fear and great joy, <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;departed&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> ran to tell his disciples. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:9">9</span></font></b> And behold, Jesus met them, saying, &ldquo;Greetings!&rdquo; And they came up <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came up&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> took hold of his feet and worshiped him. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:10">10</span></font></b> Then Jesus said to them, &ldquo;Do not be afraid! Go tell my brothers that they should go to Galilee, and there they will see me.&rdquo; </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:11">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:11">11</span></font></b> And <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were going&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> they were going, behold, some of the guard of soldiers went into the city <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;went&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> reported to the chief priests everything that had happened. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:12">12</span></font></b> And <i>[after they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[after]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;had assembled&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> had assembled with the elders and had taken counsel, they gave a rather large sum of money to the soldiers, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:13">13</span></font></b> telling <i>[them]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> &ldquo;Say &apos;His disciples came during the night <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;came&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> stole him <i>[while]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[while]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the temporal genitive absolute participle (&ldquo;were sleeping&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> we were sleeping.&apos; <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:14">14</span></font></b> And if this <i>[matter]</i> is heard before the governor, we will satisfy him and <u>keep you out of trouble</u>.&rdquo;<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Literally &ldquo;make you free from care.&rdquo;"><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span>  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:15">15</span></font></b> So they took the money <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;took&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> did as they were told, and spread abroad this report among the Jews until this very day. </p>
<p spacebelow="5" metadata="28:16">  <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:16">16</span></font></b> So the eleven disciples proceeded to Galilee, to the mountain which Jesus had designated for them. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:17">17</span></font></b> And <i>[when they]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[when]</i>&rdquo; is supplied as a component of the participle (&ldquo;saw&rdquo;) which is understood as temporal."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> saw him, they worshiped <i>[him]</i>,<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here the direct object is supplied from context in the English translation."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> but some doubted. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:18">18</span></font></b> And Jesus approached <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;approached&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> spoke to them, saying, &ldquo;All authority in heaven and on earth has been given to me. <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:19">19</span></font></b> Therefore, go<font size=4>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="As a participle of attendant circumstance this participle carries imperatival force picked up from the main verb (&ldquo;make disciples&rdquo;)."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> <i>[and]</i><font size=6>&nbsp;</font><span metadata="Here &ldquo;<i>[and]</i>&rdquo; is supplied because the previous participle (&ldquo;go&rdquo;) has been translated as a finite verb."><font color="blue"><sup shift="-4">@</sup></font></span> make disciples of all the nations, baptizing them in the name of the Father and of the Son and of the Holy Spirit, <b><font color="#969696"><span metadata="28:20">20</span></font></b> teaching them to observe everything I have commanded you, and behold, I am with you all the days until the end of the age.&rdquo; </p>
